[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to this course about the Magnus Queen's Gambit!  This course is a complete repertoire for Black against 1. d4, based on the Queen's Gambit with an early ...a6. This is sometimes called the Janowski Variation or simply the “a6-QGD”. Simply put, it's a classical and solid opening with a slight twist.  Personally I have always liked investigating the lesser trodden paths in the opening phase, which the Magnus Queen's Gambit certainly is. At the same time, it is important for me to play correct chess, and I would never play or recommend something that I consider inferior. This balance of being somewhat unusual but still sound is what attracted me to the opening in the first place.  Of course, as the name suggests, a big source of inspiration comes from the current World Champion. He time and again shows that the classical and solid structures that arise in the opening leave plenty of room for outplaying his opponents. Although the opening is often named after Dawid Janowski, who played it more than 100 years ago, I decided to call this course The Magnus Queen's Gambit, as it really is Magnus who brought it back to popularity in the modern age.  For the last couple of years I have analyzed and played the opening myself a lot, using it both to get an interesting fighting game against weaker opponents as well as to neutralize stronger opponents. What I have come to appreciate more and more in the opening is how the play revolves much more about understanding, experience and general concepts rather than concrete lines.  It is my firm belief that when studying openings, one should always aim to improve the middlegame and endgame as well. While there are some concrete lines, sometimes even pretty or funny ones, the main focus of the course revolves around explaining the typical motifs and plans for both sides. Especially compared to other Chessable courses, including even my own previous course on the Ruy Lopez, the number of lines is a lot less, while I often continue showing some instructive games a bit longer.  A slightly unusual feature of this course, and one that I really like myself, is that against numerous White lines I recommend two different options for Black, of a rather different style and attitude. This gives you an opportunity to adjust the course more to your personal preferences and style, which I believe can be very useful.  The Magnus Queen's Gambit, despite having recently gained in popularity, is still a relatively unexplored territory in opening theory. Therefore it was possible to find a lot of new and exciting ideas, even very early on in the opening. Some of them I've tried in my own games, and some are still waiting to be tried!  I believe the opening is suited especially well for those who prefer to spend a little less time on opening theory in general, and who are not afraid of trying out some new things. Stylistically it's a robust and healthy opening, with the pawn structure often fixed, but surprisingly often Black can also choose to turn it dynamic very quickly. In comparison to my previous course on the Ruy Lopez, I would say that the recommended target group is still of a very wide range  (as I always try to make it)  but if anything, perhaps a tad easier to digest than my Ruy Lopez, as the number of lines are simply much lower. Still, since the course was previously published on GingerGM, I've had people ranging from ~1400 up to Grandmasters telling me how they felt it fit perfectly to their level!  A few words about the move from GingerGM to Chessable. This course was originally published in December 2020 on the GingerGM website. The main part of this course is still the same. I have looked over the lines again, and am still recommending the same lines, as I believe them still to work fine. However, even if the Magnus Queen's Gambit is not the most topical opening, theory has still moved forward quite a bit. Therefore, I have updated the lines quite a bit, covering some new options for White and expanding on some things where theory has moved on a lot. Additionally, I have focused on improving all verbal explanations a lot, to make it clearer and more understandable. In my original work in 2020, the opening was so fresh that not a lot of material was published about it at all.   In updating the course, I also had a look at the recommendations of recent years, with the most notable courses being Max Warmerdams Janowski Variation and Sam Shanklands 1. d4 repertoire. Warmerdam and I are in some variations recommending the same lines, but in all the mainlines we are recommending different options. Many different playable options seems to me a nice indicator of the soundness and richness of the opening!  Nils Grandelius  26 May 2022. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Two Knights - (Provocative Option) Mainline: 5...h6, 6.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nc3 a6
{ The move that constitutes the Magnus Queen's Gambit, or the Janowsky Variation. Not developing a piece is of course provocative, but as already mentioned, by having the stronghold on d5 we can allow ourselves such liberties. The idea of ...a6 is to threaten to take the pawn on c4, and then defend it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ The mainline. White avoids the threat of ...dxc5 in the most brutal manner. }
4... exd5
{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight, as the c1-bishop could still go to g5 in case we play ...Nf6. This position could also be reached if White started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  a6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  . }
5... h6
{ Another provocation! I really like this move, actually. It looks super weird to make another pawn move on the flank, but there is a very concrete idea behind it. The idea is simply to develop with ...Nf6 on the next move, and avoid the Bg5-pin. The point is that White has no good way of opening up the position fast, giving us time for such extravagance.  Basically, we are narrowing White's different options quite a lot, and our next moves will often be automatic. Still, it's perfectly understandable if you find this a bit too provocative, so  5...Nf6  will also be recommended. }
6. Bf4
{ The main move. As Bg5 is no longer an option there is no other reasonable square for the bishop. White has a few more direct ways, which we will consider later. }
6... Nf6 { Continuing to develop. } 7. e3 Bd6
{ Here we see one of our main points. The bishop goes to d6 in one move, without stopping on e7 first. The trade of dark-squared bishops in the Carlsbad structure generally favors Black, as the White bishop is very active. Additionally, our queen will be rather well placed on d6, controlling the important e5-square. }
8. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ From now on, there are two important questions. The first one is the eternal question for this repertoire – will we be able to develop our c8-bishop in a convenient way?   The other one, which applies more specifically to this exact position, is on which sides the kings will castle. Most often, both sides castle short, but it is worth keeping in mind that both sides actually also still have the possibility of castling long. }
9. Bd3
{ The most natural move, preventing our bishop from being developed to f5. }
9... O-O
{ The main move. Compared to our alternative, 9...Bg4, we commit the king to the kingside and give White time to prevent  10.h3  , preventing  10...Bg4  .  On the other hand, while we don't yet commit to ...Bg4, we are still ready to go there next move in a better version, for example if White commits to O-O next. }
10. h3
{ 10.Qb3  was played by the Armenian grandmaster Melkumyan against no one less than Magnus himself!  10...Nc6  actually transposes to the5...h6 Sidelines chapter. }
10... Nc6
{ This might look a bit funny, but is in fact a brilliant idea. We make use of not having played ... Be6 yet, trying to trade it immediately on f5. For this, we need our knight on e7! }
11. O-O Ne7 12. Qc2
{ The typical move, hindering Bf5 for the time being!  12.Na4  Bf5  is just a better version for Black.   and  12.Rc1  doesn't change things as  12...Bf5  is still a good move. }
12... g6
{ ...But we insist. It is absolutely not necessary to remember any of what now follows in the notes, but I imagine it could be very useful to read them to get an idea of the typical plans and manouvers for both sides. }
13. Ne5
{ This is also a typical idea, but here it is not well-timed as Black has a counterstroke. }
13... c5
{ Using the fact that the knight is hanging on e5 to create counterplay in the centre. }
*

