13. Na4 { A good move, as c5 is an excellent outpost for the knight. } 13...
Bf5 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. Nc5 Rfb8
{ This looks very funny and requires some explanation. The point is that white is building a lot of his play around the strong c5-knight, often supported by a pawn on b4. If we go  15...Rab8  instead, then we can never really move the pawns on b7 and a6, making the knight on c5 very annoying. With our rooks on a8 and b8 though, we can play both ...b6 and ...a5 at any convenient moment. Magnus Carlsen himself played a very similar rook move against Giri. }
16. b4 c6
{ Of course both sides have plenty of options here, so I am just showing a logical way of how the game can develop: }
17. a4 Qc7 { Will be similar. } 18. Rab1 Nd6
{ White can't get b5 in due to our strong d6-knight, so he will have to switch to kingside play as in themainline. }
