{ Very important. We need to worry about the d5-pawn after White has castled.  11...Nd7?  12.Nxd5  Now surprisingly works for White.  12...Qd8  13.Ne5!  Saves the piece and keeps the pawn.  13...c6  14.Nxd7  Qxd7  15.Nb6+-  Bxb3  16.Nxd7  and it's a clear pawn up for White. }
12. Qc2 { 12.h4  h6=  Now there is no Bh3! } 12... Nd7
{ Black is absolutely fine. We have the bishop pair and a solid structure. Next up, simply ...Nf6, ...c6 etc with a very pleasant position. }
13. e4 { Looks critical, but isn't really. } 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nf6
{ Is not scary at all. White is certainly active enough to be equal, but not more than that. }
