{ Of course there is no reason to play a move like ...h6 once White has already comitted to Bf4. }
6. e3 Bd6
{ This is of course the most natural move, but this is not quite the same as with the knight already committed to f3. }
7. Bg5
{ A very smart move. It looks strange to lose a tempo like this, but the big thing is that knight is not yet comitted to f3, meaning it will find a much more comfortable spot on e2. }
7... Be6
{ Continuing in the same spirit as the mainlines.  7...c6?!  8.Bd3  is known to be pleasant for White with the pawn on a7, but here the extra move ...a6 isn't really useful at all so White is still better. }
8. Bd3 Nbd7 9. f4
{ Has been played a fair few times by decent players. It's an interesting idea, but Black gets a lot of counterplay. }
9... h6 10. Bh4
{ 10.Bxf6  Nxf6  makes no sense for White as our bishop pair is very strong here. }
10... g5
{ Necessary to not get rolled over by the pawns. Now it gets very sharp, but also very interesting! }
11. fxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Bxh2
{ The position is a truly weird one. It's equal material and White's pawn structure is a bit broken, but we are also having some issues with the pin on the h-file and lack of development.  12...Bg3+?!  doesn't really help as  13.Kd2  leaves the White king safe on the queenside. }
13. Kf1 Rg8 { This is another way of getting out of the pin. } 14. Nf3 Bd6
{ Looks safe enough. And if we are safe, we are likely also better, as White's structure isn't great. }
