5. g3
{ This is a fairly common move at club levels. It isn't so bad, but also not very good. The point is that we place our central pawns on d5 and c6, creating a barrier against the Catalan bishop. In a usual Catalan, the main issue for Black is the development of the light squared bishop, but having already traded pawns on d5, we have no such problems here. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg2 c6 { Placing the pawn on the best square immediately. } 7. Nf3
{ Similar positions are discussed in the 5...h6 mainlines. Here we did not yet have to play ...h6, so it should be a slightly better version. }
7... Be7
{ We simply develop our pieces to sensible squares, and it isn't so easy for White to create a good plan. The usual idea would be to break with e4, but here that will mainly create a weak isolated d-pawn. }
