[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. Nbd2
{ An interesting move. Our last move clearly intended to grab the pawn on c4, so white simply defends it! The downside is that d2 is a somewhat passive square for the knight, as it inflicts less influence of the centre than from c3, and blocks the bishop from c1. Now we have a big choice. }
4... Nf6
{ This is the lazy move. In itself it's perfectly natural of course, but the big danger here is that we are running into normal positions where the move ...a6 isn't really very useful at all.  4...c5  is the interesting suggestion from Max Warmerdam in his Janowsky course. }
5. g3 { 5.e3  transposes to the 4.e3line. } 5... c5
{ This is the way. A very good rule of thumb in these positions is to look for ways to get ...c5 in once White has committed the knight to d2. It is now likely that we get an isolated pawn on d5, and then the knight would be much stronger on c3, putting pressure on the d5-pawn.  5...Be7  6.Bg2  O-O  7.O-O  something like this would be a good illustration of what we are trying to avoid. In this typical Catalan position, the move ...a6 doesn't really serve any purpose so White is just enjoying a nice version here. }
6. Bg2 { 6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bg2  Nc6  will be the same. } 6... Nc6 7. O-O
{ In order to put pressure, White should be aware of this idea. } 7... cxd4
{ The simplest, immediately settling for the isolated pawn. } 8. cxd5 exd5
{ This is important. If we recapture with a piece on d5 white will pick up the d4-pawn with Nb3 after which the Catalan bishop on g2 will be very very strong. Now we are settled with a somewhat worse structure, but with very active piece play and a bit of a space advantage.  8....Qxd5  9.Nb3  e5  doesn't work due to  10.Nfxd4  with a discovered attack against the queen. }
9. Nb3 Bd6
{ Due to White's smart move order we were not able to place our bishop on the more active a7-g1 diagonal. }
10. Nfxd4 { This is another attempt. } 10... O-O 11. Be3
{ White's idea is to capture on c6 and take control of the c5-square. } 11...
Bg4 { The most active move. } 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Rc1 Rc8
{ Our structure is slightly broken on the queenside, but we do have some potential for counterplay on the kingside, with the typical ...Qd7, ...Bh3 idea, but also pushing the h-pawn up the board! }
14. Bc5
{ Is another normal way of handling the situation. Trading dark squared bishops is in general beneficial for White, but it also takes some time. }
14... Re8 15. Re1 h5
{ Preparing the typical counterplay in these positions. Please note how far the b3-knight is from the defense on the kingside! }
