[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "3.Nf3 4th Move Sidelines: 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. e3
{ Clearly the most serious of the 4th move alternatives. White is trying to build up in a sort of Colle-style setup with b3, Bb2, Bd3, O-O and Nbd2 or Nc3.  4.cxd5  exd5  will transpose to the mainlines, as White really should play Nc3 here or within the next few moves. }
4... Nf6
{ Basically on our next move we have two ways of playing. We can either try to strike against White's centre immediately, trying to equalize by concrete means. The other option is to choose a setup of how we develop our pieces, and just stick to it. Both options are equally viable, but I quite like the latter option, especially as it goes very well together with our repertoire against alternatives to 2. c4. }
5. Nc3
{ This can also be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nc3  a6  4.e3  Nf6  5.Nf3  . }
5... Nbd7
{ This is a very smart move-order to reach our preferred setup!  5...dxc4  is the big mainline and fine for Black, but not an area we are forced to enter.   5...b6  would actually be inaccurate here, due to the very annoying  6.cxd5!  exd5  7.Qa4+!?  and we lack one tempo to get harmony, the main problem being that  7...Nbd7?!  is met by  8.Qc6!  winning a pawn. }
6. b3
{ 6.Bd3?!  dxc4!  would simply win a tempo compared to taking on c4 on move 5. }
6... b6 { Now we can just stick to our usual developing scheme. } 7. Bd3 Bb7 8.
O-O Bd6
{ This is our setup. Both our bishops points towards the White kingside. By later playing ...Ne4 we can follow up with ...f5, and really start to bring a lot of pieces over. It's important to note that all this is possible due to our centre being so solid, making it harder for White to create meaningful counterplay. }
9. Bb2 O-O
{ This is the tabiya of the line, and a position likely to be reached in practice. Many possible moves can now be played for both sides, but I do not believe there is any need to know theory at all. The important thing is to understand the general plans and ideas. I'll give some lines just to show the ideas, but it is certainly not necessary to remember any of it by heart. }
10. Qc2 { Trying to push e4. } 10... dxc4
{ This is a smart reply once the queen has left d1. } 11. bxc4 c5
{ Gives nice counterplay in the centre. } 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5
{ After  13.cxd5  b5  our pawns are much more mobile here. Simply pushing them gives us a rather promising initiative. }
13... Bxd5
{ It's slightly unusual to give up the bishop pair like this, but the important thing is to get our pawns going without delay. }
14. cxd5 b5 { Followed by ...c4, with excellent counterplay. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines: 3.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ This is actually tricky and should be treated with care! White is trying to play the Catalan, but we can't respond with our usual capture on c4, as White did not put a pawn there yet.  3.Bg5  makes no sense in our move order.  3...Be7  4.Bxe7  Qxe7=  and as is often the case in such positions, the most likely thing to happen is we get positions similar to 3. Nf3 / 4.Bg5, but without having wasted time playing ...a6. }
3... b6
{ Once again we are making use of the tempo gained by not playing ...Nf6. This time we use it to get our bishop to the long diagonal in time.  3...c5  is a decent move and the suggestion of Warmerdam in his Janowsky course, but it leads to mainlines that are in my opinion somewhat outside the scope of our repertoire, and I prefer to avoid them.   3...b5!?  such provocative moves can be played, but to be honest I have always doubted the strength of it. To me, it looks like White should be better.   3...Nf6  4.c4  would be a real Catalan, something we have no intention of entering. }
4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O Nd7
{ Important!  5...Nf6?!  6.Ne5!  is unpleasant. After  6...Nbd7  7.c4  Nxe5  8.dxe5!  attacks the knight on f6. }
6. Nfd2
{ Looks funny but is a typical idea in the Catalan. The idea is that for White to make the e4-break happen the knights are needed on c3 and d2. }
6... Ngf6 7. c4 Be7 { Just sticking to our natural development. } 8. Nc3 O-O 9.
e4 { White's idea, but it is not really enough to bother us. } 9... Nxe4 10.
Ndxe4 dxe4 11. Nxe4
{ If White would have time to complete development he could maybe lay claim to a very small edge, but here we can immediately strike. }
11... c5 { Which seems to equalize comfortably. } 12. d5 exd5 13. cxd5
{ is not a scary passed pawn as we have it well under control. } 13... Nf6
{ Forces trades or retreating. } 14. Nc3 Bd6 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. Ne4
Qd8
{ The d-pawn is securely blocked and as likely to be a weakness as a strength. }
*

