[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Psuedo-Trompowsky: 2.Bg5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Bg5
{ Frankly speaking a pretty bad move. Any normal developing move will lead to a pleasant position, but personally I like to punish White. }
2... f6
{ I understand this looks a bit unnatural, and it is a very concrete move. I think it leads to an edge for Black, but if you don't feel like it's worth it to study theory after 2. Bg5, then any other move is perfectly sensible as well. For example,  2...h6  3.Bh4  c6  just setting up a solid centre. After  4.Nd2  Bf5  our bishop is outside the pawn chain, this is very solid for Black. However, it's a lot less fun than our mainline! }
3. Bh4
{ 3.Bf4  is not quite the Jobava-London with colours reversed, as we can still play ...c5 before ...Nc6. Again, White has basically just wasted one tempo by moving the bishop twice. }
3... Nh6
{ This is the big point. With the bishop on h4 we can attack it immediately with a knight on f5. }
4. e3
{ This has been the most common move in practical play, but it simply doesn't work. }
4... Nf5 5. Bg3 h5
{ Threatening to win the bishop. In fact, black is already clearly better! } 6.
h4 Nxg3 7. fxg3 { This is a positional disaster for White. } 7... Qd6
{ Forcing either the knight to the clumsy e2-square or the king out. } 8. Kf2
e5 { We have the centre, the two bishops and the better pawn structure. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter"]
[Black "Jobava London: 2.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nc3
{ The Veresov. Generally speaking the sidelines on move 2 works better for White against 1...Nf6 than 1...d5, as we now often can make use of not having our knight on f6 yet. }
2... Bf5
{ I like this a lot! Usually we have to struggle a lot to develop our bishop so easily, but here we get a chance to do it 'for free'. The only downside of this is that White can now attack our bishop with f3 and g4, but I think it does more harm than good to White's position.  2...c5  is another good moves, but it allows  3.e4!?  dxe4  4.d5  which is fine for Black but not to everyone's taste. }
3. f3
{ Clearly the critical move. The only way to 'punish' ...Bf5 is to attack it with e4 or g4. }
3... Nf6 { Now necessary, in order to stop e4. } 4. Bf4
{ The most common move for White, reaching a real Jobava London. } 4... e6
{ Inviting the pawn push. } 5. g4
{ The most logical and by far the main move. } 5... Bg6 6. h4
{ White is trying to roll us over on the kingside, so please take note of our response, as it is a very typical and strong one: }
6... h5 { Forcing the kingside to be blocked. } 7. g5 Nfd7
{ with ...e6 already on the board, we can safely retreat our knight here. The point now is that with the blockade on the kingside we can safely castle short and begin to attack on the queenside and in the centre without having to worry about our king. }
8. e4 dxe4 9. fxe4 Bb4
{ Sees White being overextended. The e4-pawn is hanging, but we are also ready to strike in the centre with ...e5! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1a) Two Knights - 5...h6 (Provocative Option) Mainline"]
[Black "Two Knights 5...h6 Mainline: Avoid: 10...Be6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nc3 a6
{ The move that constitutes the Magnus Queen's Gambit, or the Janowsky Variation. Not developing a piece is of course provocative, but as already mentioned, by having the stronghold on d5 we can allow ourselves such liberties. The idea of ...a6 is to threaten to take the pawn on c4, and then defend it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ The mainline. White avoids the threat of ...dxc5 in the most brutal manner. }
4... exd5
{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight, as the c1-bishop could still go to g5 in case we play ...Nf6. This position could also be reached if White started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  a6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  . }
5... h6
{ Another provocation! I really like this move, actually. It looks super weird to make another pawn move on the flank, but there is a very concrete idea behind it. The idea is simply to develop with ...Nf6 on the next move, and avoid the Bg5-pin. The point is that White has no good way of opening up the position fast, giving us time for such extravagance.  Basically, we are narrowing White's different options quite a lot, and our next moves will often be automatic. Still, it's perfectly understandable if you find this a bit too provocative, so  5...Nf6  will also be recommended. }
6. Bf4
{ The main move. As Bg5 is no longer an option there is no other reasonable square for the bishop. White has a few more direct ways, which we will consider later. }
6... Nf6 { Continuing to develop. } 7. e3 Bd6
{ Here we see one of our main points. The bishop goes to d6 in one move, without stopping on e7 first. The trade of dark-squared bishops in the Carlsbad structure generally favors Black, as the White bishop is very active. Additionally, our queen will be rather well placed on d6, controlling the important e5-square. }
8. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ From now on, there are two important questions. The first one is the eternal question for this repertoire – will we be able to develop our c8-bishop in a convenient way?   The other one, which applies more specifically to this exact position, is on which sides the kings will castle. Most often, both sides castle short, but it is worth keeping in mind that both sides actually also still have the possibility of castling long. }
9. Bd3
{ The most natural move, preventing our bishop from being developed to f5. }
9... O-O
{ The main move. Compared to our alternative, 9...Bg4, we commit the king to the kingside and give White time to prevent  10.h3  , preventing  10...Bg4  .  On the other hand, while we don't yet commit to ...Bg4, we are still ready to go there next move in a better version, for example if White commits to O-O next. }
10. h3
{ 10.Qb3  was played by the Armenian grandmaster Melkumyan against no one less than Magnus himself!  10...Nc6  actually transposes to the5...h6 Sidelines chapter. }
10... Be6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Qc2 Rac8 13. Rac1 c5
{ Is the plan for instance Mickey Adams likes to do in such positions. } 14.
dxc5 Nxc5
{ Black has an isolated pawn, but no bad pieces and no weaknesses apart from that. It should be fine for black, but still I can't help to think it's a little bit sad and doesn't give as many long-term counterchances as I would like. }
*

