{ Here we see one of our main points. The bishop goes to d6 in one move, without stopping on e7 first. The trade of dark-squared bishops in the Carlsbad structure generally favors Black, as the White bishop is very active. Additionally, our queen will be rather well placed on d6, controlling the important e5-square. }
8. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ From now on, there are two important questions. The first one is the eternal question for this repertoire – will we be able to develop our c8-bishop in a convenient way?   The other one, which applies more specifically to this exact position, is on which sides the kings will castle. Most often, both sides castle short, but it is worth keeping in mind that both sides actually also still have the possibility of castling long. }
9. Bd3
{ The most natural move, preventing our bishop from being developed to f5. }
9... O-O
{ The main move. Compared to our alternative, 9...Bg4, we commit the king to the kingside and give White time to prevent  10.h3  , preventing  10...Bg4  .  On the other hand, while we don't yet commit to ...Bg4, we are still ready to go there next move in a better version, for example if White commits to O-O next. }
10. h3
{ 10.Qb3  was played by the Armenian grandmaster Melkumyan against no one less than Magnus himself!  10...Nc6  actually transposes to the5...h6 Sidelines chapter. }
10... Nc6
{ This might look a bit funny, but is in fact a brilliant idea. We make use of not having played ... Be6 yet, trying to trade it immediately on f5. For this, we need our knight on e7! }
11. O-O Ne7 12. Qc2
{ The typical move, hindering Bf5 for the time being!  12.Na4  Bf5  is just a better version for Black.   and  12.Rc1  doesn't change things as  12...Bf5  is still a good move. }
12... g6
{ ...But we insist. It is absolutely not necessary to remember any of what now follows in the notes, but I imagine it could be very useful to read them to get an idea of the typical plans and manouvers for both sides. }
13. g4 { This is too much. } 13... h5 14. g5 Ne8
{ This is a positional disaster for White. } *

