[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1a) Two Knights - 5...h6 (Provocative Option) Mainline"]
[Black "Two Knights 5...h6 Mainline: 9.Bg4 (Alternative) #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nc3 a6
{ The move that constitutes the Magnus Queen's Gambit, or the Janowsky Variation. Not developing a piece is of course provocative, but as already mentioned, by having the stronghold on d5 we can allow ourselves such liberties. The idea of ...a6 is to threaten to take the pawn on c4, and then defend it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ The mainline. White avoids the threat of ...dxc5 in the most brutal manner. }
4... exd5
{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight, as the c1-bishop could still go to g5 in case we play ...Nf6. This position could also be reached if White started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  a6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  . }
5... h6
{ Another provocation! I really like this move, actually. It looks super weird to make another pawn move on the flank, but there is a very concrete idea behind it. The idea is simply to develop with ...Nf6 on the next move, and avoid the Bg5-pin. The point is that White has no good way of opening up the position fast, giving us time for such extravagance.  Basically, we are narrowing White's different options quite a lot, and our next moves will often be automatic. Still, it's perfectly understandable if you find this a bit too provocative, so  5...Nf6  will also be recommended. }
6. Bf4
{ The main move. As Bg5 is no longer an option there is no other reasonable square for the bishop. White has a few more direct ways, which we will consider later. }
6... Nf6 { Continuing to develop. } 7. e3 Bd6
{ Here we see one of our main points. The bishop goes to d6 in one move, without stopping on e7 first. The trade of dark-squared bishops in the Carlsbad structure generally favors Black, as the White bishop is very active. Additionally, our queen will be rather well placed on d6, controlling the important e5-square. }
8. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ From now on, there are two important questions. The first one is the eternal question for this repertoire – will we be able to develop our c8-bishop in a convenient way?   The other one, which applies more specifically to this exact position, is on which sides the kings will castle. Most often, both sides castle short, but it is worth keeping in mind that both sides actually also still have the possibility of castling long. }
9. Bd3
{ The most natural move, preventing our bishop from being developed to f5. }
9... Bg4
{ White's move order allows Black to play ...Bg4. Generally speaking, one can say that the trade of Black's bishop for the white f3-knight leads to positions that are a bit dryer and easier to handle for both. It is not really better or worse, but rather a matter of taste what one prefers. }
10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nbd7
{ 11...O-O  would be a mistake! After giving up the bishop on f3, we have lost control of the crucial e4-square meaning that White's pawn push on the kingside gains in strength.  12.O-O-O  Nbd7  13.g4  c5  14.h4  shows White being ahead in his attack. }
12. O-O O-O
{ With both sides having castled short we are happy. The light-squared bishop is generally our problem piece in this structure, so having traded it off makes it easier to coordinate the rest of our forces. Since creating the original course for GingerGM, I've had this position rather many times in rapid and blitz, with excellent results. We put our pawn on c6, and then long term, if allowed, try to transfer the knight from d7 to d6. A well-timed ...Ne4 jump is also always on the cards. }
