4. cxd5
{ The mainline. White avoids the threat of ...dxc5 in the most brutal manner. }
4... exd5
{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight, as the c1-bishop could still go to g5 in case we play ...Nf6. This position could also be reached if White started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  a6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  . }
5... h6
{ Another provocation! I really like this move, actually. It looks super weird to make another pawn move on the flank, but there is a very concrete idea behind it. The idea is simply to develop with ...Nf6 on the next move, and avoid the Bg5-pin. The point is that White has no good way of opening up the position fast, giving us time for such extravagance.  Basically, we are narrowing White's different options quite a lot, and our next moves will often be automatic. Still, it's perfectly understandable if you find this a bit too provocative, so  5...Nf6  will also be recommended. }
6. Qb3
{ As usual an interesting attempt, trying to attack us before we have completed the development. }
6... Nf6
{ Can also be reached via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1pp2ppp/p7/3p4/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Nf6  6.Qb3  h6  . }
7. e4
{ This is a very dangerous attempt from white. White is trying to kill us before we have gotten our pieces out!  7.Bf4  Bd6  8.Bxd6  Qxd6  9.e3  O-O  transposes to 6.Bf4. }
7... Nxe4
{ 7...dxe4??  8.Ne5  would immediately lose!  8...Qe7  9.Bc4++  and we can't defend f7. }
8. Qxd5
{ Is a solid attempt from white to gain a slight advantage in the ending, but I don't really believe black is worse at all. }
8... Nxc3
{ The choice of both myself and Magnus in our games!  8...Qxd5  9.Nxd5  Bd6  10.Bd3  Nf6  11.Nxf6+  gxf6  is the other way to play. While it's probably ok, I don't really like to weaken my pawn structure. }
9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. bxc3 Be6
{ It might look unpleasant with the king stuck in the centre, but the queens are traded off and long term we have the better structure.  10...Bd6  to quickly get ...Re8+ is also a reasonable idea. }
11. Bd3 Nc6 12. O-O Bd6
{ This is another solid setup, but we have a good response. } 13. c4 Nb4 14.
Be2 Re8 { With counterplay. } 15. a3 Bd7
{ Hitting the e2-bishop, works very well for Black. } *

