{ Here we see one of our main points. The bishop goes to d6 in one move, without stopping on e7 first. The trade of dark-squared bishops in the Carlsbad structure generally favors Black, as the White bishop is very active. Additionally, our queen will be rather well placed on d6, controlling the important e5-square. }
8. Be5 { This is actually a very tricky attempt. } 8... c6
{ Forced, as Bxf6 followed by Nxd5 was a threat. } 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O Re8
{ 10...Bg4?!  would be an excellent move had the bishops already been traded on d6, but here it works less well  11.h3!  Bxf3  12.Qxf3  The bishop is now excellently placed on e5, putting pressure on f6.  12...Bxe5  13.dxe5  Nfd7  14.Qf5  g6  15.Qf4  This is very dangerous for Black. }
11. h3
{ A cunning waiting move. White wants us to move our queen before taking on d6, trying to win a tempo. }
11... Bxe5 { This is a good antidote. } 12. Nxe5 c5
{ This is a typical way of making use of the knight hanging on e5 to create counterplay. Next we can either trade on d4 followed by challenging the knight on e5 for a solid position, or go more aggressive with ...c4!? followed by b5-b4. }
