{ Here many moves has been tried, but the good thing for us is that we can almost always play the same plan against everything! ...Bd6, ...c6, ...Qc7 and ...O-O. }
8. Bd3
{ 8.h3  Bd6  will be the same. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1ppn1ppp/p3bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be2  is simply a less active square for the bishop.  8...Bd6  We can continue in exactly the same spirit. }
8... c6 { This is an interesting move order, avoiding the annoying 9. Bf4. } 9.
O-O
{ 9.Qc2  Bd6  will transpose, and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1n1ppp/p1p1bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2NBPN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h3  Bd6  10.Bf4  Qc7  will be the same. }
9... Bd6 10. Nd2
{ is an interesting idea I have faced in the Ragozin opening. White wants to push f4-f5. Here we have not yet castled yet though, meaning we can try to counterattack on the kingside. }
10... Qc7 11. f4 h6
{ Very logical. Now we are the ones trying to attack on the kingside! } 12. Bh4
g5 13. Bg3 Bg4
{ An important move, otherwise our bishop would be trapped on e6! } 14. Qe1
O-O-O
{ Bringing the king to safety. The position is now very double-edged. White is going to attack us on the queenside, with a timely b4-b5 push, but we have plenty of counterplay on the kingside and along the e-file. Very interesting, but I certainly wouldn't mind playing black here. }
*

