7. e3 { The mainline. } 7... Nbd7
{ Here many moves has been tried, but the good thing for us is that we can almost always play the same plan against everything! ...Bd6, ...c6, ...Qc7 and ...O-O. }
8. Bd3
{ 8.h3  Bd6  will be the same. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1ppn1ppp/p3bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be2  is simply a less active square for the bishop.  8...Bd6  We can continue in exactly the same spirit. }
8... c6 { This is an interesting move order, avoiding the annoying 9. Bf4. } 9.
O-O
{ 9.Qc2  Bd6  will transpose, and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1n1ppp/p1p1bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2NBPN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h3  Bd6  10.Bf4  Qc7  will be the same. }
9... Bd6 10. Bf4
{ This is actually White's best move. By moving the bishop to f4 before Black plays ...Qc7 White is saving on the move Qd2, and can place the queen on the optimal square c2 after the trade of bishops. }
10... Qc7 { 10...Bxf4  11.exf4  is again a structure I would prefer to avoid. }
11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. h3 O-O
{ This is the main tabyia of the 5...Nf6  line. From here on we certainly don't need to know any more moves by heart, but it is again very useful to have a look at the lines given, to get an idea of the typical plans and setups for both. One important difference compared to what we have seen in the 5...h6 line, is that we still have our pawn on h7. This makes it even more attractive for black to to play g6, as it is well defended. The knight is already on d7, meaning it can't go via c6 to e7. Instead, to achieve our preferred trade of bishops on f5 we need a knight on d6 or g7. Basically both knights have the option of going to d6  @@StartBracket@@via f6-e8 or b6-c8@@EndBracket@@ and it's a matter of taste which one to prefer. I'd say it's slightly more natural to use the d7-knight but both are fine, really. }
13. Qb3
{ This has actually been played by both Giri and Magnus himself. The idea is to push the a-pawn and have the possibility of Qa3 later on, but it is certainly not enough to scare us. }
13... Rfb8
{ This was played by Carlsen himself!  13...g6  is possible immediately as well - basically, Black has plenty of decent options. }
14. a4 a5
{ The rook is more useful on a8 than f8 when the action is happening on the queenside. This also looks fine for Black. }
15. Rfc1 g6 { Beginning the typical manouver. } 16. Nd2 Ne8 { The right plan! }
17. Ne2 Qe7 18. Nf4 Nd6 19. Qa3 Bf5
{ We have gotten everything we wanted! ½-½ Giri,A @@StartBracket@@2764@@EndBracket@@-Carlsen,M @@StartBracket@@2863@@EndBracket@@ chess24.com INT 2020 }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2a) Two Knights - 5...Nf6 (Mainstream Option) Mainline"]
[Black "Two Knights 5...Nf6 Mainline: Avoid 13...Rac8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nc3 { 3.Nf3  a6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  is the same! } 3... a6
{ The move that constitutes the Magnus Queen's Gambit, or the Janowsky Variation. Not developing a piece is of course provocative, but as already mentioned, by having the stronghold on d5 we can allow ourselves such liberties. The idea of ...a6 is to threaten to take the pawn on c4, and then defend it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ The mainline. White avoids the threat of ...dxc5 in the most brutal manner. }
4... exd5
{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight, as the c1-bishop could still go to g5 in case we play ...Nf6. This position could also be reached if White started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  a6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  . }
5... Nf6
{ The big alternative to  5...h6  . In practice Nf6 has been much more common. The main advantage is of course that it finally develops a piece instead of just moving pawns. Another more subtle advantage though, and one which we will discuss, is that the move h6 in itself could often become a weakness later in the middlegame. There are two main downsides of starting with Nf6 though: the most important is that we allow the immediate pin with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p4n2/3p4/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg5  , and the other that it's a much more common move, making it more likely our opponents are familiar with it and will be less provoked :-@@EndBracket@@ }
6. Bg5 Be6
{ The main downside of allowing the immediate 6.Bg5 is that we have to develop the bishop to e6 this early, thereby losing a tempo later once we trade it on f5. }
7. e3 { The mainline. } 7... Nbd7
{ Here many moves has been tried, but the good thing for us is that we can almost always play the same plan against everything! ...Bd6, ...c6, ...Qc7 and ...O-O. }
8. Bd3
{ 8.h3  Bd6  will be the same. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1ppn1ppp/p3bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be2  is simply a less active square for the bishop.  8...Bd6  We can continue in exactly the same spirit. }
8... c6 { This is an interesting move order, avoiding the annoying 9. Bf4. } 9.
O-O
{ 9.Qc2  Bd6  will transpose, and @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p1n1ppp/p1p1bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2NBPN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.h3  Bd6  10.Bf4  Qc7  will be the same. }
9... Bd6 10. Bf4
{ This is actually White's best move. By moving the bishop to f4 before Black plays ...Qc7 White is saving on the move Qd2, and can place the queen on the optimal square c2 after the trade of bishops. }
10... Qc7 { 10...Bxf4  11.exf4  is again a structure I would prefer to avoid. }
11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. h3 O-O
{ This is the main tabyia of the 5...Nf6  line. From here on we certainly don't need to know any more moves by heart, but it is again very useful to have a look at the lines given, to get an idea of the typical plans and setups for both. One important difference compared to what we have seen in the 5...h6 line, is that we still have our pawn on h7. This makes it even more attractive for black to to play g6, as it is well defended. The knight is already on d7, meaning it can't go via c6 to e7. Instead, to achieve our preferred trade of bishops on f5 we need a knight on d6 or g7. Basically both knights have the option of going to d6  @@StartBracket@@via f6-e8 or b6-c8@@EndBracket@@ and it's a matter of taste which one to prefer. I'd say it's slightly more natural to use the d7-knight but both are fine, really. }
13. Qc2 Rac8 14. Rac1 Rfe8 15. a3 g6
{ This has been more common in practice. It is an equally viable alternative, but delaying the trade of the bishops gives slightly more options for White. With the rooks on c8 and e8 Black will have to use the manouver Nh5-g7 to trade the bishops instead. }
16. Rfe1 Qe7 17. b4 { This is a way to apply some pressure. } 17... Nh5
{ 17...b5  18.Nd2  Nb6  19.Nb3  is nice for White with the strong c5-Knight.   @@StartFEN@@2r1r1k1/1p1nqp1p/p1p1bnp1/3p4/1P1P4/P1NBPN1P/2Q2PP1/2R1R1K1 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  17...Nb6  18.Qb2!?  is followed by pushing a4-b5. }
18. Na4 Ng7 19. Nc5
{ Shows why the knight is better on d6 than g7. The pawn on b7 is hanging, and White will have an easier job pushing b5 }
19... Rc7 20. a4 Bf5 21. Nxd7 Bxd3 22. Qxd3 Qxd7 23. b5
{ This is very slightly worse for Black, but we can't say that he has fully equalized yet. }
