8. Bd3
{ 8.h3  Bd6  will be the same. @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1ppn1ppp/p3bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@  8.Be2  is simply a less active square for the bishop.  8...Bd6  We can continue in exactly the same spirit. }
8... Bd6 { Is the more common move order. } 9. Bf4
{ This is a cunning move order, because now we don't have time to protect the bishop with the queen from  c7  .  9.h3  c6  10.Bf4  Qc7  11.Bxd6  Qxd6  12.O-O  tranposes to our main line. }
9... Bxf4
{ Changing the pawn structure, but with a specific idea in mind.  9...Qe7  is too clumsy, as the queen really belongs to c7 }
10. exf4
{ A possible trade for Black, but generally speaking we are trying to avoid this structure. The doubled pawns gives white firm control of e5 and potential to push f4-f5 later on. }
10... Bg4
{ A concrete move. If we get to trade on f3 undisturbed we have nothing to complain about. }
11. Qe2+ { This is a bit disturbing though. } 11... Kf8
{ This is slightly risky, but not bad. I personally prefer to start with @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1ppn1ppp/p3bn2/3p2B1/3P4/2NBPN2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8...c6  , but it's really a matter of taste. }
12. h3
{ 12.O-O-O  Qe8  is fine, as we either get to trade queens or leave White with a tripled pawn! }
12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qe7+ { Important, to disturb White's coordination. } 14.
Kf1 Qb4 { Continuing the concrete approach. } 15. Nxd5
{ The only move, as both b2 and d4 were hanging. } 15... Qxd4 16. Nxf6 Nxf6 17.
g4 g6 18. Kg2 Kg7
{ A rather unusal position has arisen. We have a nice 3 vs 2 on the queenside, but White has a slight lead in development and some potential to attack our king. All in all rather messy, but seems OK. }
*

[Event "?"]
