[Round "?"]
[White "2b) Two Knights - 5...Nf6 (Mainstream Option) Sidelines"]
[Black "Two Knights 5...Nf6 Sidelines: 6.Qb3 / 7.dxc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nc3 a6
{ The move that constitutes the Magnus Queen's Gambit, or the Janowsky Variation. Not developing a piece is of course provocative, but as already mentioned, by having the stronghold on d5 we can allow ourselves such liberties. The idea of ...a6 is to threaten to take the pawn on c4, and then defend it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ The mainline. White avoids the threat of ...dxc5 in the most brutal manner. }
4... exd5
{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Nf3
{ Developing the knight, as the c1-bishop could still go to g5 in case we play ...Nf6. This position could also be reached if White started with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp2ppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.Nf3  a6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Nc3  . }
5... Nf6
{ The big alternative to  5...h6  . In practice Nf6 has been much more common. The main advantage is of course that it finally develops a piece instead of just moving pawns. Another more subtle advantage though, and one which we will discuss, is that the move h6 in itself could often become a weakness later in the middlegame. There are two main downsides of starting with Nf6 though: the most important is that we allow the immediate pin with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1pp2ppp/p4n2/3p4/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bg5  , and the other that it's a much more common move, making it more likely our opponents are familiar with it and will be less provoked :-@@EndBracket@@ }
6. Qb3
{ Is always an option for White in these positions. Next up is Bg5, creating pressure against the d5-pawn. Here, we have the option of transposing to 5...h6 by playing  6...h6  here, but we also have another tempting move: }
6... c5
{ Remember this idea! As soon as the queen goes to b3, the pawn on d4 is weakened so it's very often tempting to put pressure on it. Additionally, ...c4 will come with tempo later.  6...h6  transposes to 5...h6. }
7. dxc5 { Leaves us with an IQP, but: } 7... Bxc5 8. Bg5 d4
{ Shows the downside of moving the queen too early in the opening. Black is taking over the initiative here. }
9. Ne4 Be6 { Gives another tempo and: } 10. Qxb7 Ra7 { Traps the queen! } *

