2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nc3 a6
{ The move that constitutes the Magnus Queen's Gambit, or the Janowsky Variation. Not developing a piece is of course provocative, but as already mentioned, by having the stronghold on d5 we can allow ourselves such liberties. The idea of ...a6 is to threaten to take the pawn on c4, and then defend it with ...b5. }
4. cxd5
{ The mainline. White avoids the threat of ...dxc5 in the most brutal manner. }
4... exd5
{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Qb3
{ Once again an early Qb3 is a dangerous attempt that needs to be taken seriously. }
5... Nf6
{ This is very rare and very interesting, but also riskier than 5...c5.  5...c6  6.e4!  is White's point, giving them a nice initiative. }
6. Bg5 c5
{ This is almost a new idea! We allow white to settle us with doubled f-pawns, but we get the bishop pair and a lot of activity as compensation.  6...c6  7.e4!  also gives White a dangerous initiative here! }
7. Bxf6
{ Certainly the critical attempt, as if  7.Nf3  we can choose if we want to transpose to ...c4 or ...Nc6. }
7... gxf6 { 7...Qxf6  8.Nxd5  would be a disaster for Black! } 8. Nf3 Nc6
{ 8...c4!?  is also possible, but I prefer to keep the position as open as possible with the two bishops.  9.Qc2  Nc6  10.g3!  is the best setup for White. }
9. dxc5 { The most direct try, but as usual rather risky. } 9... Bxc5
{ 9...d4?  10.O-O-O  is not the same as before, as we don't have our strong ...Be6 followed by ...Nd7 idea.  10...Be6  11.Qxb7! }
10. e3
{ Trying to keep control, but then White should really have played e3 a move earlier. }
10... Be6 11. Rd1 Qb6
{ It might feel a bit counterintuitive to trade queens, but the point is that it makes it much easier for us to push d4 through. }
12. Qxb6 Bxb6 13. Be2 O-O-O { Followed by ...d4, with excellent bishops. } 14.
Nd4
{ This would stop us from going ...d4. This isn't the only idea for Black however! }
14... Nxd4 15. exd4 Kb8
{ This is very healthy for us. Without the doubled f-pawns we would certainly have an edge, but here it is compensated for by the bishop pair, pressure against the d4-pawn and potential for play along the c-file by moving the king and going ...Rc8. }
*

