{ Now we have reached the so-called Carlsbad structure. One of the oldest and most classical structures in chess, and one which I consider essential to study for ones chess development in general. Our version is slightly different than the most common. The move ...a6 is not traditionally considered the most useful move for Black, but on the other hand, White has committed to cxd5 earlier than perhaps wanted. An important point is that our knight is not yet on f6, so Bg5 is not an option for White yet. Another point is that our bishop is still on f8, meaning it can go to either e7 or d6 in one move, depending on circumstances. }
5. Qb3
{ Once again an early Qb3 is a dangerous attempt that needs to be taken seriously. }
5... Nf6
{ This is very rare and very interesting, but also riskier than 5...c5.  5...c6  6.e4!  is White's point, giving them a nice initiative. }
6. Bg5 c5
{ This is almost a new idea! We allow white to settle us with doubled f-pawns, but we get the bishop pair and a lot of activity as compensation.  6...c6  7.e4!  also gives White a dangerous initiative here! }
7. Bxf6
{ Certainly the critical attempt, as if  7.Nf3  we can choose if we want to transpose to ...c4 or ...Nc6. }
7... gxf6 { 7...Qxf6  8.Nxd5  would be a disaster for Black! } 8. Nf3 Nc6
{ 8...c4!?  is also possible, but I prefer to keep the position as open as possible with the two bishops.  9.Qc2  Nc6  10.g3!  is the best setup for White. }
9. dxc5 { The most direct try, but as usual rather risky. } 9... Bxc5
{ 9...d4?  10.O-O-O  is not the same as before, as we don't have our strong ...Be6 followed by ...Nd7 idea.  10...Be6  11.Qxb7!  loses for us now. }
10. Nxd5
{ Again the critical try, but I would be super scared to enter such a line as White.  10.O-O-O  will transpose to the mainline after  10...Be6  11.Nxd5  Nd4! }
10... Be6 11. O-O-O
{ Now if White is allowed to consolidate he will be winning, but we have a very interesting idea at our disposal! }
11... Nd4 { Blocking the rook's path to d5. } 12. Nxd4 Bxd5
{ We are a pawn down, but it is not felt at all in this crazy position. If White is careful he will manage to get into an equal ending, but it certainly looks fun for Black! The following lines are of course based on computer analysis, but I think it is enough for a game to say that Black has excellent compensation for the pawn and White is the one who has to play better to equalize. }
13. Qe3+ Be6 14. Qc3
{ This is one of the most solid ways for White, but it's rather tricky to find. }
14... Bxd4 15. Rxd4 Qb6 { Threatening ...Rc8. } 16. Kb1 Rc8 17. Qb4
{ And with the help of trades, White is surviving! } 17... Qc6 18. Qd2 Ke7
{ A good move. The king is much safer on e7 than on the kingside, and additionally it helps us play ...Rhd8 next. }
19. e3 Rhd8
{ We have excellent compensation for a mere pawn. White should look for a way to give it back and equalize. }
*

