{ Threatening an unpleasant fork on c2. } 11. Bxc4
{ A sharp move, and White's only real try. } 11... Nc2+ 12. Kd1 Qxe4 13. Nxe4
Nxa1
{ We are a rook up, but the knight on a1 will be lost. That leaves us with an exchange for a pawn. The best way to handle the situation is to give back another pawn in order to finish development. }
14. Re1 Be6 15. Neg5 { Building up the pressure. } 15... Be7
{ This is how to react. We give back another pawn on e6, but are able to complete development in the meantime. }
16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bxe6 Nf6 18. Bd2
{ Traps the knight on a1. White will then have two pawns for the exchange but the rooks are strong in such an open position. }
18... a5 19. Kc1 Bb4
{ Trading the bishops followed by ...Kd8 and ...Re8 is at the very least not worse for Black. }
