5. Bf4
{ Compared to playing  5.Nf3  first this has some differences. By putting the bishop immediately on f4 White can no longer play Bg5 in one go, but on the other hand, delaying Nf3 gives White the often very decent possibility of putting the knight on e2 instead. }
5... Nf6
{ Of course there is no reason to play a move like ...h6 once White has already comitted to Bf4. }
6. e3 c5
{ The most straightforward move, and certainly the one I like the most! However, if you really don't want to memorize any theory at all, then  6...Bd6  is a slightly passive but very solid alternative.   6...c5  is also the move advocated by Max Warmerdam, so I think it is fair to say that it's objectively the strongest. The reason ...c5 is tempting here is that White has already committed the bishop to f4, thereby losing a tempo if he later puts it on g5 to increase the pressure on the d5-pawn. }
7. Bd3
{ This was recently played against me in two games in the same Titled Tuesday, so very topical! }
7... cxd4
{ This is the simplest choice.  7...c4?!  I am quite sceptical about pushing ...c4 when White can put his bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal. From c2, the bishop exerts a lot of control over the crucial e4-square.  8.Bc2  b5  9.a3  Be7  10.Nf3  Bb7  11.Ne5  Nc6  12.Qf3  for example.   7...Nc6  was my own choice in the games, but it is a bit less accurate as White is in time to play  8.Nge2  cxd4  9.Nxd4  Nxd4  10.exd4  after which the remaining knights will be slightly better for White, as White's knight is attacking  d5  where as Black's is only defending. }
8. exd4 Bd6
{ This is immediately just an equal position with both sides having a solid setup. }
9. Nge2 O-O { Simply developing naturally. } 10. O-O Nc6 11. Qd2 Re8
{ It's symmetrical of course, but with a lot of pieces still on the board gives plenty of room for both sides to try taking over the initiative. It is true that the e2-knight is perhaps slightly more flexibly placed than our knight on f6, but that is really a very minor details. Without any problematic pieces ourselves the position can't be other than equal. }
*

