{ The most straightforward move, and certainly the one I like the most! However, if you really don't want to memorize any theory at all, then  6...Bd6  is a slightly passive but very solid alternative.   6...c5  is also the move advocated by Max Warmerdam, so I think it is fair to say that it's objectively the strongest. The reason ...c5 is tempting here is that White has already committed the bishop to f4, thereby losing a tempo if he later puts it on g5 to increase the pressure on the d5-pawn. }
7. Nge2
{ This move might look very strange at first sight, but once we understand that generally, g2 is the best square for White's bishop, then it makes a lot of sense to place the knight on a square where it isn't blocking the g2-bishop. }
7... Nc6
{ 7...c4?!  8.g3  shows White's idea. The bishop gets to  g2  without the knight being in the way on  f3  . }
8. Rc1
{ White is playing a waiting game, trying to get us to commit our bishop to e6 before playing g3. }
8... h6
{ We make our own waiting move!  8...Be6?!  9.g3!  and we lose a tempo if we go  9...Bg4  .   8...Bg4?!  is also not what we want. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nxd5 { This is not something that bothers us! } 10... Nxd5 11.
Rxc5 Be6
{ Leaving us with plenty of compensation and potential play against the white queenside. }
12. Bg3 O-O { We will pick up at least one of White's queenside pawns. } *

