{ This is a fairly common move at club levels. It isn't so bad, but also not very good. The point is that we place our central pawns on d5 and c6, creating a barrier against the Catalan bishop. In a usual Catalan, the main issue for Black is the development of the light squared bishop, but having already traded pawns on d5, we have no such problems here. }
5... Nf6 6. Bg2 c6 { Placing the pawn on the best square immediately. } 7. Nh3
{ Some very decent players have experimented with this move. I guess the point is to be able to build up a centre with f3 and e4 later. }
7... Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. f3
{ Or else the knight doesn't really do anything on h3. But it doesn't really work out for White. }
9... c5
{ The move to remember. In this structure it's almost always a good idea after White plays f3 to immediately attack the centre with ...c5. If White were to take on c5, then their dark squares are very weak. There is no doubt Black is better here. }
