4... Be7
{ 4...f6?!  Magnus himself played this move once in a very similar position once against Jon Ludvig Hammer in Norway Chess, but it is simply too weakening.  4...Nf6  5.e3  would show White's idea - c4 is protected with the bishop outside the pawn chain, so we would not have managed to disturb White's setup by 3...a6. This is still a reasonable Queen's Gambit Declined, but something White would be comfortable with and outside the scope of our repertoire. }
5. Bxe7
{ It looks harmless to spend two tempi trading a piece and letting us develop with tempo, but White's logic is simple: he just wants to get his pieces out to normal squares and hope that the slight space advantage and the potentially bad light squared bishop on c8 gives him an edge. We should be careful here to not end up in a not-so-much-worse but slightly depressing position. }
5... Nxe7
{ An interesting alternative to the more common recapture with the queen. The knight is usually better on f6, but in this way, we gain some time for development, which we can use to strike quickly in the centre. }
6. Nbd2
{ Just as against 5... Qxe7, this is the critical way of developing.  6.Nc3  Nd7  and White should play  7.e3  transposing to6. e3. }
6... O-O 7. e3
{ is similar to 6.e3 but with the knight on a slightly worse square. The main difference for us is that we shouldn't take on c4 anymore, as White can then recapture with the knight. }
7... Nd7 8. Rc1 { 8.Be2  c5  is immediately fine. } 8... b6 9. b4
{ The critical move, fighting against our main idea with ...c5.  9.cxd5  Nxd5=  White will not be able to stop our ...c5-break. }
9... c6
{ This is not necessary, but a very interesting positional idea. The point is to play ...a5,  and after White's reply b5 we can advance with our c-pawn to c5 without white being able to capture it en passant!  9...Bb7  10.Be2  c5  gets the break in and once again leads to a lot of trades, for instance  11.bxc5  bxc5  12.O-O  cxd4  the simplest  13.Nxd4  dxc4  14.Nxc4  Bd5  White's knights are looking very active, but we don't have any weaknesses and our pieces are sensibly placed, so it's just equal. }
10. cxd5 exd5
{ With our pawn already on b6 we can't play in our usual fashion with Nf6 and Bf5, but as White has already comitted his pawn to b4 we can create counterplay on the queenside with the a5-push. }
11. Bd3 a5 { Inviting the pawn to advance further. } 12. a3
{ Also reasonable. } 12... Ba6 13. Bxa6 Rxa6 14. b5
{ The only move to try to disturb our setup, but also a typical idea in the QGD. }
14... cxb5 15. Qe2 { We can't defend b5. } 15... Ra7 16. Qxb5 Rc7
{ Fighting for the c-file. } 17. O-O Qb8
{ Preparing ...Rfc8. Had the d2-knight been on b5 instead White would probably have a nice edge, but as it is, White lacks a little harmony with the d2-knight especially being passive. This, combined with the c-file compensates for our slightly worse structure. }
