[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. Bg5
{ For a long time I considered  4.Bg5  to be a very solid but not at all ambitious move for White. The big point of 4. Bg5 is of course to develop the bishop, but more specifically here White wants to protect the c4-pawn @@StartBracket@@which we intend to take after 3...a6!@@EndBracket@@ by the most natural move e3, so 4. Bg5 simply develops the bishop with tempo giving time to play e3 next. One of the world's absolute best theoreticians, Grandmaster Anish Giri, recently played this against me in Titled Tuesday, which is a great testimony to the strength of the move. }
4... Be7
{ 4...f6?!  Magnus himself played this move once in a very similar position once against Jon Ludvig Hammer in Norway Chess, but it is simply too weakening.  4...Nf6  5.e3  would show White's idea - c4 is protected with the bishop outside the pawn chain, so we would not have managed to disturb White's setup by 3...a6. This is still a reasonable Queen's Gambit Declined, but something White would be comfortable with and outside the scope of our repertoire. }
5. Bxe7
{ It looks harmless to spend two tempi trading a piece and letting us develop with tempo, but White's logic is simple: he just wants to get his pieces out to normal squares and hope that the slight space advantage and the potentially bad light squared bishop on c8 gives him an edge. We should be careful here to not end up in a not-so-much-worse but slightly depressing position. }
5... Nxe7
{ An interesting alternative to the more common recapture with the queen. The knight is usually better on f6, but in this way, we gain some time for development, which we can use to strike quickly in the centre. }
6. Nbd2
{ Just as against 5... Qxe7, this is the critical way of developing.  6.Nc3  Nd7  and White should play  7.e3  transposing to6. e3. }
6... O-O 7. g3
{ Fianchettoing the bishop makes a lot of sense combined with the knight on d2 here. The knight defends c4 and supports a later e4-break, further opening up for the bishop on g2. }
7... Nd7 8. Bg2 c5
{ I like this move a lot. White does still have a few ways to make the game dry, but the most natural move leads to very interesting play. }
9. O-O
{ 9.cxd5  Nxd5  transposes to our line after both  10.Rc1  and  10.O-O  . }
9... b5
{ This is the idea of our move order! Instead of trying to equalize by just trading we are trying to gain space on the queenside and hope to get an initiative there. }
10. cxd5
{ Definitely the move for White.  10.b3  is too timid.  10...Bb7=  We have gotten a free developing move in return for the rather useless b3. }
10... Nxd5
{ Our next move would be to play ...c4, grabbing even more space on the queenside. }
11. dxc5 Nxc5
{ This is solid for White, but definitely with possibilites for both sides to take over. }
12. Rc1 Na4 { A useful idea with the pawn on b5. } *

