2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ Catalan afficionados will be very likely to play 4. g3 here. The difference between this and the Catalan is that we have our pawn on a6 instead of the knight on f6. Throughout history it was generally thought that the difference favoured us, and that the move 4. g3 is not critical at all. However, upon investigating the positions arising I have come to change my opinion and do now consider 4. g3 a very decent move for White. Still, if we know what we are doing we are certainly still fine. }
4... dxc4
{ The first move is obvious. Our entire idea of playing 3...a6 is to take on c4 next if White doesn't defend it, and here he didn't! }
5. Bg2 { Now Black has a very important choice. } 5... Nc6
{ People inclined to take risks would probably like playing this move, which is very reminiscent of 'real' Catalan lines, with the difference that the knight is not yet committed to f6. The knight is not badly placed on f6, but here we have an extra tempo for developing the queenside first which is important. It is definitely a better version than the similar one from the Catalan. If one has some experience in the Catalan then this would be an excellent choice for sure. If not, then it is still very interesting but riskier.   5...Nc6  is also the recommendation of Max Warmerdam in his Janowsky course here on Chessable. I believe we can conclude that in an objective sense, it is the best move, although as I have so often stressed throughout the course, personal preferences and stylistic choices are way more important than objective evaluations here. }
6. O-O Rb8 7. e4 { This is critical. } 7... Be7 8. Nc3 Nf6
{ Now we have actually transposed to real a real Catalan. It is far from one of the most critical ways White can play there, but compared to our 3...a6 repertoire it is probably the most mainstream variation of the entire repertoire! }
9. Qe2 b5
{ Grabbing space and protecting our extra pawn. These sort of positions are very complicated strategically. White has a very strong center but we have managed to keep our extra pawn on c4 and lack other weaknesses. Careful play is required to avoid White getting a successful break in the centre, but with precision we are fine. I do repeat though, that this is real Catalan theory, so there exists considerably more theory than in most other parts of our repertoire.  9...Nxd4?!  10.Nxd4  Qxd4  11.Rd1  followed by e5 is known to give White a dangerous initiative. }
10. Rd1 O-O 11. Bf4
{ This was played by the British grandmaster Peter Wells, but he did not really achieve anything. }
11... Nb4
{ A typical move for these positions. Not only aiming at the d3-square, but more importantly stepping out of Whites d5-push, which is by far the most important thing to watch out for here. }
12. Ne1 Re8
{ Another very typical move. As White will sooner or later have to play d5 to prove compensation, our rook will be useful on the e-file. }
13. a3 Nc6 14. d5 exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 Bd6
{ White will likely be able to win back the pawn by doubling on the d-file, but we are ready to play …Qe7 and develop the c8-bishop, after which our pieces are simply better placed than our opponents. }
