{ Here our extra tempo makes a huge difference. In the Catalan, Black has to suffer much more to keep the extra pawn, whereas here we can do it in a harmonious way. }
8. b3 cxb3 9. axb3
{ This is a reasonable way for White to play to get some compensation, but certainly not more than that. We have some slightly vulnerable pawns on the queenside, but the knight enjoys an excellent outpost on b4 and the kingside can be developed safely next. }
9... Bb7 10. Nc3
{ A tricky move order from White. By delaying  Bb2  he keeps the option of going  Ba3  in one go, in case we put our knight on  b4  too early. For  10.Qe2  see our 8.Qe2 line. }
10... Bb4
{ 10...Nb4?!  11.Ne5!  is a bit unpleasant when we don't have ...Qd5+ after the bishop trade. }
11. Bb2 Nf6 12. Ne5 { This wins back the pawn to reach an equal ending } 12...
Nxe5 13. Bxb7 Rxb7 14. dxe5 Qxd1 { The simplest is just to trade more stuff. }
15. Rfxd1 Bxc3 16. Bxc3 Nd7 17. Rxa6 Ke7
{ We had to give back our extra pawn, but in doing so we were allowed some trades, freeing up our position. Additionally, it should be noted that our king is better in the centre than having castled, as it's an ending so it should be active! White is still slightly more active, but our pawn structure is definitely the better one here. }
