7... b5
{ Here our extra tempo makes a huge difference. In the Catalan, Black has to suffer much more to keep the extra pawn, whereas here we can do it in a harmonious way. }
8. b3 cxb3 9. axb3
{ This is a reasonable way for White to play to get some compensation, but certainly not more than that. We have some slightly vulnerable pawns on the queenside, but the knight enjoys an excellent outpost on b4 and the kingside can be developed safely next. }
9... Bb7 10. Nc3
{ A tricky move order from White. By delaying  Bb2  he keeps the option of going  Ba3  in one go, in case we put our knight on  b4  too early. For  10.Qe2  see our 8.Qe2 line. }
10... Bb4
{ 10...Nb4?!  11.Ne5!  is a bit unpleasant when we don't have ...Qd5+ after the bishop trade. }
11. Ne4 { The most dangerous attempt. } 11... Nf6 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6
{ Now we would be very happy if we got a move to stabilize, but White can immediately attack us! }
13. Ne1 { 13.Bb2  O-O  would be very comfortable for us. } 13... O-O 14. Qc2
{ This leads to interesting complications! } 14... e5
{ This protects the c6-knight by the queen. A solid bailout option would be  14...Bxe1  15.Bxc6  Bxc6  16.Qxc6  Bb4  17.Rxa6  Bd6  . }
15. Nd3 { After the most natural reply to ...e5, we have a nice trick! } 15...
e4 { This leads to a complicated fight! } 16. Nf4 Bd6
{ White will grab the e4-pawn but all our remaining pieces are very active giving us loads of counterplay. }
17. Nd5 Qg6 18. Bxe4 f5 19. Bg2 Qf7
{ Threatening ...Nxd4 and preparing to bring the knight to the kingside via d8-e6. It's a weird structure, and a weird position in general, but I believe in our chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8b) 3.Nf3, 4.g3 (Solid Option)"]
[Black "3.Nf3 / 4.g3 Solid Option: Avoid 5...a6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... Nf6
{ This is just to show the comparison between the 'real' Catalan and 5...Nc6. }
4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 a6
{ 5...c5  6.O-O  cxd4  7.Nxd4  a6  would be a road to the mainline, but White could have taken with the Queen on  d4  . }
6. O-O Nc6 7. e3 Rb8
{ 7...b5  8.Ne5!  Nxe5  9.Bxa8!  shows why the tempo gained by omitting Nf6 is so important!   7...Bd7  common move, but leaving the bishop misplaced.  8.Qe2  b5  9.b3  cxb3  10.axb3  supposed to be decent compensation. }
8. Nfd2 b5 9. Bxc6+ { 8...b5 is too late as this comes before Bb7. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8b) 3.Nf3, 4.g3 (Solid Option)"]
[Black "3.Nf3 / 4.g3 Solid Option: 6.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ Catalan afficionados will be very likely to play 4. g3 here. The difference between this and the Catalan is that we have our pawn on a6 instead of the knight on f6. Throughout history it was generally thought that the difference favoured us, and that the move 4. g3 is not critical at all. However, upon investigating the positions arising I have come to change my opinion and do now consider 4. g3 a very decent move for White. Still, if we know what we are doing we are certainly still fine. }
4... dxc4
{ The first move is obvious. Our entire idea of playing 3...a6 is to take on c4 next if White doesn't defend it, and here he didn't! }
5. Bg2 { Now Black has a very important choice. } 5... c5
{ The solid approach. We try to trade material in the centre. } 6. Be3
{ This is a normal move in the Catalan, but here we can once again make use of not having played Nf6 yet! }
6... Ne7 { Hits the bishop from f5. } 7. Nc3 Nf5
{ White has to play accurately in order to not be worse! } 8. d5 Nxe3 9. fxe3
{ This is hardly very trustworthy. We are fine in various ways! } 9... b5
{ I like this ambitious attempt, possibly even followed by ...Ra7, covering the important f7-square! }
*

