[Black "3.Nf3 / 4.g3 Solid Option: 6.O-O / 7.Qxd4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ Catalan afficionados will be very likely to play 4. g3 here. The difference between this and the Catalan is that we have our pawn on a6 instead of the knight on f6. Throughout history it was generally thought that the difference favoured us, and that the move 4. g3 is not critical at all. However, upon investigating the positions arising I have come to change my opinion and do now consider 4. g3 a very decent move for White. Still, if we know what we are doing we are certainly still fine. }
4... dxc4
{ The first move is obvious. Our entire idea of playing 3...a6 is to take on c4 next if White doesn't defend it, and here he didn't! }
5. Bg2 { Now Black has a very important choice. } 5... c5
{ The solid approach. We try to trade material in the centre. } 6. O-O cxd4 7.
Qxd4 { This is solid, but hardly scary. } 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 e5
{ A key point in our setup. We want to be able to put our knight on c6 and our bishop on e6. }
9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Nbd2 f6
{ Logical after Nbd2, as the pawn chain f6/e5 will hinder both White's knights.  10...Nf6  11.Nxc4  does not work now, as e5 would be hanging.   10...Be6  11.Ng5  is a big issue. }
11. Nxc4 Be6 12. b3 Rd8
{ The last important move. By covering the square on d6 we can play ...Nge7 without a nasty Nd6+. Next we Just go Nge7-d5 and then develop the kingside. White lacks any pawn breaks to create play and therefore the position is just equal. }
