{ If we now give White another tempo for development he would have a fantastic Catalan position with a super strong g2-bishop, but luckily for us, we are just in time to develop our queenside. }
9... b5 { An absolutely essential move. } 10. Qb3
{ 10.Qd3  Bb7  is very similar. } 10... Bb7 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. a4
{ The critical way of playing, as we are now forced to put our b-pawn on a dark square. }
12... b4 13. Bg5
{ The bishop is actually White's worst piece here, as the knights are much better equipped at exploiting our queenside weaknesses. Therefore it is a good idea for White to play Bg5xf6 here. }
13... Bc5
{ Immediately forcing White to make a decision with his d4-knight.  13...Nbd7  14.Bxf6  Nxf6  is possible as well, but I like it less. The point is that all action is going to happen on the queenside, so therefore we want our knight to stay closer to the action. From d7 the knight can continue to c5, whereas on f6 it is in fact slightly out of play. }
14. Bxf6
{ The critical move. It might look unpleasant to get a doubled f-pawn, but White has all his pieces ready to play on the queenside, so it doesn't really matter. }
14... gxf6 15. Qf3 Qxf3
{ These endings can sometimes be a bit sad for Black, but here we have pretty decent counterplay. We will go ...Ke7, ...Nd7 and ...Rhc8, after which we either fight for the c-file or try to attack White's pawns on b2 and a4. The doubled f-pawn doesn't matter as White can't really attack it at all. }
16. Nxf3 Nd7 17. Nbd2 Ke7 18. Rac1 Rhc8
{ Looks completely fine. Next up we can double rooks on the c-file or bring the knight to b6 or c5. White theoretically speaking has slightly the better structure, but our activity compensates fully for that. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8b) 3.Nf3, 4.g3 (Solid Option)"]
[Black "3.Nf3 / 4.g3 Solid Option: 6.O-O / 7.Nxd4 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ Catalan afficionados will be very likely to play 4. g3 here. The difference between this and the Catalan is that we have our pawn on a6 instead of the knight on f6. Throughout history it was generally thought that the difference favoured us, and that the move 4. g3 is not critical at all. However, upon investigating the positions arising I have come to change my opinion and do now consider 4. g3 a very decent move for White. Still, if we know what we are doing we are certainly still fine. }
4... dxc4
{ The first move is obvious. Our entire idea of playing 3...a6 is to take on c4 next if White doesn't defend it, and here he didn't! }
5. Bg2 { Now Black has a very important choice. } 5... c5
{ The solid approach. We try to trade material in the centre. } 6. O-O cxd4 7.
Nxd4 Nf6
{ 7...e5?  8.Nf3  Qxd1  9.Rxd1  Compared to7. Qxd4, White got an extra move, Rd1, which we can't allow!  9...Nc6  10.Nbd2!  f6  11.Nxc4  Be6  12.b3  and Rd1 is a huge tempo to have gained here, as Nd6+ will soon be on the agenda! }
8. Qa4+
{ This is a very smart check. By moving the queen White stops our idea of playing ...e5 and trading queens. }
8... Qd7
{ 8...Nbd7  is unfortunately too slow:  9.Rd1!  e5?!  10.Nf5  followed by the very annoying Nd6+. }
9. Qxc4
{ If we now give White another tempo for development he would have a fantastic Catalan position with a super strong g2-bishop, but luckily for us, we are just in time to develop our queenside. }
9... b5 { An absolutely essential move. } 10. Qb3
{ 10.Qd3  Bb7  is very similar. } 10... Bb7 11. Bxb7 Qxb7 12. a4
{ The critical way of playing, as we are now forced to put our b-pawn on a dark square. }
12... b4 13. Bg5
{ The bishop is actually White's worst piece here, as the knights are much better equipped at exploiting our queenside weaknesses. Therefore it is a good idea for White to play Bg5xf6 here. }
13... Bc5
{ Immediately forcing White to make a decision with his d4-knight.  13...Nbd7  14.Bxf6  Nxf6  is possible as well, but I like it less. The point is that all action is going to happen on the queenside, so therefore we want our knight to stay closer to the action. From d7 the knight can continue to c5, whereas on f6 it is in fact slightly out of play. }
14. Bxf6
{ The critical move. It might look unpleasant to get a doubled f-pawn, but White has all his pieces ready to play on the queenside, so it doesn't really matter. }
14... gxf6 15. Nf3
{ Keeping the queens makes a lot of sense for White, but despite the doubled pawns our king is still very safe. }
15... Nd7 16. Qc4 Rc8 17. Qh4
{ This is not very threatening with so few other pieces in proximity to our king. }
17... h5
{ Even this is possible. It is simply not possible for White to generate dangerous threats. }
18. Nbd2 Kf8 19. Ne4 Be7 20. Rfd1 Kg7
{ With the queen on h4 we can even begin to think about counterattacking on the queenside with Rc2 next. }
*

