{ Immediately forcing White to make a decision with his d4-knight.  13...Nbd7  14.Bxf6  Nxf6  is possible as well, but I like it less. The point is that all action is going to happen on the queenside, so therefore we want our knight to stay closer to the action. From d7 the knight can continue to c5, whereas on f6 it is in fact slightly out of play. }
14. Bxf6
{ The critical move. It might look unpleasant to get a doubled f-pawn, but White has all his pieces ready to play on the queenside, so it doesn't really matter. }
14... gxf6 15. Nf3
{ Keeping the queens makes a lot of sense for White, but despite the doubled pawns our king is still very safe. }
15... Nd7 16. Nbd2 Rc8 17. Rac1 O-O
{ We are fine. The doubled f-pawns is a slight annoyance, but our pieces are active and there are a few ideas to fight for the initiative ourselves. Moving the bishop to e7 next would open up for Nc5, but also preparing ...f5 and ...Bf6 as an idea to attack White's pawns. All in all 4.g3 is a very decent variation for White, and we need to choose on move 5 how much risk we are willing to take. I like going aggressive with 5... Nc6, but playing it solidly with 5...c5 certainly makes a lot of sense as well and I will most probably alternate between the two. }
