3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. Nbd2
{ An interesting move. Our last move clearly intended to grab the pawn on c4, so White simply defends it! The downside is that d2 is a somewhat passive square for the knight, as it inflicts less influence of the centre than from c3, and blocks the bishop from c1. Now we have a big decision to make. }
4... dxc4
{ This is the move I have always played myself. It is rather concrete in nature, and aims at equalizing by concrete means.  4...c5  is Max Warmerdam's approach. It is some kind of mix between our lazy and aggressive option, but certainly also interesting and with good chances of equalizing. }
5. Nxc4 b5 6. Nce5 { By far the most logical move. } 6... Bb7
{ The structure is somewhat unusual for our repertoire. In general, we are trying to get the c5-break in, but we do need to be a bit careful because the b5-pawn could turn out to be a bit weak. }
7. e3
{ 7.Ng5  is an empty shot as we can defend with  7...Nh6  after which the knights will be kicked back. }
7... Nf6 { 7...c5?!  is another option, but too risky for my taste. } 8. Qc2
{ This is a tricky move, as it increases control over the crucial c5 and c6-squares. }
8... Nfd7
{ Remember this idea! The fight is all about the squares on c6 and c5, therefore the knight is actually doing more on b8 than on f6!  8...Nbd7  9.Nc6  would be exactly what White wants. }
9. Nd3 Bd6 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Qe7
{ Followed by ...c5 gives us our typical play. } *

