4... dxc4
{ This is the move I have always played myself. It is rather concrete in nature, and aims at equalizing by concrete means.  4...c5  is Max Warmerdam's approach. It is some kind of mix between our lazy and aggressive option, but certainly also interesting and with good chances of equalizing. }
5. Nxc4 b5 6. Nce5 { By far the most logical move. } 6... Bb7
{ The structure is somewhat unusual for our repertoire. In general, we are trying to get the c5-break in, but we do need to be a bit careful because the b5-pawn could turn out to be a bit weak. }
7. e3
{ 7.Ng5  is an empty shot as we can defend with  7...Nh6  after which the knights will be kicked back. }
7... Nf6 { 7...c5?!  is another option, but too risky for my taste. } 8. a4
{ The critical move, immediately highlighting our main problem: the b5-pawn. }
8... Ne4
{ Again a key resource. White's lack of development means we do not have to defend our queenside passively, but can instead go for the counterattack! }
9. Nd2
{ 9.Bd3  Bb4+  10.Nd2  is the same as starting with 9.Nd2.   9.axb5  Bb4+  transposes to7.a4. }
9... Bb4 { Increasing the pressure. } 10. Nd3
{ The critical try. White is forcing us to give up our dark squared bishop and then taking control of the c5-square to stop us breaking there. He as good chances of succeeding with the idea, but it also neglects the development giving us possibilites to fight for the initiative }
10... Bxd2+ { 10...Nxd2  11.Bxd2  Bd6  is also possible but less interesting. }
11. Bxd2 O-O
{ A critical position. Having given up the bishop on d2 we now struggle to break with c5, but we still have our strong bishop on b7, making it hard for White to develop the f1-bishop. An additional idea that often is interesting is to capture bxa4, further weakening our own pawn structure but giving counterplay along the b-file. }
12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8 14. Bb4
{ This is a very straightfoward way of playing, but we can meet it well. }
14... Re8 15. Be2 c5 { Using tactical means to get the desired push in. } 16.
dxc5 Na6 17. O-O Qg5
{ This creates a lot of tactical threats and equalizes easily } 18. Bf3
{ This is a mistake! } 18... Nxb4 19. Nxb4 Rd8
{ Followed by ...Nd2 with a double attack against f3 and f1. } *

