{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. Nbd2
{ An interesting move. Our last move clearly intended to grab the pawn on c4, so White simply defends it! The downside is that d2 is a somewhat passive square for the knight, as it inflicts less influence of the centre than from c3, and blocks the bishop from c1. Now we have a big decision to make. }
4... dxc4
{ This is the move I have always played myself. It is rather concrete in nature, and aims at equalizing by concrete means.  4...c5  is Max Warmerdam's approach. It is some kind of mix between our lazy and aggressive option, but certainly also interesting and with good chances of equalizing. }
5. Nxc4 b5 6. Nce5 { By far the most logical move. } 6... Bb7
{ The structure is somewhat unusual for our repertoire. In general, we are trying to get the c5-break in, but we do need to be a bit careful because the b5-pawn could turn out to be a bit weak. }
7. e3
{ 7.Ng5  is an empty shot as we can defend with  7...Nh6  after which the knights will be kicked back. }
7... Nf6 { 7...c5?!  is another option, but too risky for my taste. } 8. a4
{ The critical move, immediately highlighting our main problem: the b5-pawn. }
8... Ne4
{ Again a key resource. White's lack of development means we do not have to defend our queenside passively, but can instead go for the counterattack! }
9. Nd2
{ 9.Bd3  Bb4+  10.Nd2  is the same as starting with 9.Nd2.   9.axb5  Bb4+  transposes to7.a4. }
9... Bb4 { Increasing the pressure. } 10. Nd3
{ The critical try. White is forcing us to give up our dark squared bishop and then taking control of the c5-square to stop us breaking there. He as good chances of succeeding with the idea, but it also neglects the development giving us possibilites to fight for the initiative }
10... Bxd2+ { 10...Nxd2  11.Bxd2  Bd6  is also possible but less interesting. }
11. Bxd2 O-O
{ A critical position. Having given up the bishop on d2 we now struggle to break with c5, but we still have our strong bishop on b7, making it hard for White to develop the f1-bishop. An additional idea that often is interesting is to capture bxa4, further weakening our own pawn structure but giving counterplay along the b-file. }
12. Rc1
{ The most natural move. White is getting ready to meet Nd7 with the unpleasant Ba5. }
12... Nxd2 { 12...Nd7  13.Ba5!  is slightly annoying. } 13. Qxd2 bxa4
{ Looks stupid, but with the rook having left a1 it makes a lot of sense. While White recaptures the pawn we can put pressure along the b-file. I believe we do not have any problems at all here, the only issue being that it might be a little bit dry.  13...Nd7  is also possible of course, but I prefer the more direct idea of capturing on a4. }
14. Qb4 { Trying to disturb our coordination. } 14... Bc6 15. Ne5 a5
{ A useful inclusion! } 16. Qc4 Bd5 17. Qxc7 Qxc7 18. Rxc7 f6 19. Nd3 Na6
{ This gives excellent counterplay. White is still struggling to find time to develop his kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10b) 3.Nf3, 4.Nbd2 (Lazy Option)"]
[Black "3.Nf3 / 4.Nbd2 Lazy Option: 7.cxd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. Nbd2
{ An interesting move. Our last move clearly intended to grab the pawn on c4, so White simply defends it! The downside is that d2 is a somewhat passive square for the knight, as it inflicts less influence of the centre than from c3, and blocks the bishop from c1. Now we have a big choice. }
4... Nf6
{ This is the lazy move. In itself it's perfectly natural of course, but the big danger here is that we are running into normal positions where the move ...a6 isn't really very useful at all.  4...c5  is the interesting suggestion from Max Warmerdam in his Janowsky course. }
5. g3 { 5.e3  transposes to the 4.e3line. } 5... c5
{ This is the way. A very good rule of thumb in these positions is to look for ways to get ...c5 in once White has committed the knight to d2. It is now likely that we get an isolated pawn on d5, and then the knight would be much stronger on c3, putting pressure on the d5-pawn.  5...Be7  6.Bg2  O-O  7.O-O  something like this would be a good illustration of what we are trying to avoid. In this typical Catalan position, the move ...a6 doesn't really serve any purpose so White is just enjoying a nice version here. }
6. Bg2 { 6.cxd5  exd5  7.Bg2  Nc6  will be the same. } 6... Nc6 7. cxd5
{ The most likely reply in practical play. } 7... exd5
{ The early trade on d5 is the most natural, but slightly less flexible than castling. }
8. O-O Bd6 9. dxc5
{ The typical reaction after we have moved our bishop from f8. } 9... Bxc5 10.
b3 { Natural development. } 10... O-O 11. Bb2 Bg4
{ This is another position that is important to understand. It might look like we have a small weakness on d5, but it's very hard for White to attack it. Especially important is, as so often, the d2-knight, which would much rather be on c3. All our pieces are actively placed and we have many natural moves next, like ...Re8, ...Qe7 and ...Rad8, with or without also playing ...Ne4 at an appropriate moment. Another thing to note is that it isn't so easy for White to trade pieces in a normal way, which otherwise would have been a wise strategy. }
*

