[White "11) 3.Nf3 4th Move Sidelines "]
[Black "3.Nf3 4th Move Sidelines: 4.e3 / 5.Nbd2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit. It's worth highlighting the main downside of 2...e6 already now – the c8-bishop is locked in. It might sound early, but that will be a key factor for many, many lines throughout the course. Generally speaking, if we solve the problem of developing the c8-bishop, we will also have a good position. }
3. Nf3
{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. e3
{ Clearly the most serious of the 4th move alternatives. White is trying to build up in a sort of Colle-style setup with b3, Bb2, Bd3, O-O and Nbd2 or Nc3.  4.cxd5  exd5  will transpose to the mainlines, as White really should play Nc3 here or within the next few moves. }
4... Nf6
{ Basically on our next move we have two ways of playing. We can either try to strike against White's centre immediately, trying to equalize by concrete means. The other option is to choose a setup of how we develop our pieces, and just stick to it. Both options are equally viable, but I quite like the latter option, especially as it goes very well together with our repertoire against alternatives to 2. c4. }
5. Nbd2
{ This move can be played with the idea of sticking to the normal setup with b3, Bb2, Bd3 next, but it can also be played as a preparation for fianchettoing the bishop with g3 next. }
5... b6
{ 5...Nbd7  is perfectly possible as well of course, but as you will see after  5...b6  6.g3  , I slightly prefer to delay the development of the queenside knight as after  6.g3  we have committed our knight to  d7  too early. }
6. g3 { The independent try. } 6... Bd6
{ A debatable decision after White's g3. Normally we say that bishops should not attack pawns defended by two other pawns @@StartBracket@@in this case g3, defended by h2 and f2@@EndBracket@@ but here I consider it more important to keep control of the e5-square and having a good square for our queen on e7.  6...Bb7  7.Bg2  Bd6  will transpose to this line. }
7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Bb7 9. e4
{ This is a thematic idea in such positions, but normally it only leads to trades. }
9... dxe4 10. Ng5
{ Winning back the e4-pawn, but we can happily give it back to equalize. }
10... Nc6 { Funny-looking, but utilizing the weakness of the d4-pawn. } 11.
Ngxe4 Be7
{ Had the White bishop been on e3 already, it might have been slightly worse, but here we have rather annoying pressure on d4, while also having completed our development. }
