9. Bb2 O-O
{ This is the tabiya of the line, and a position likely to be reached in practice. Many possible moves can now be played for both sides, but I do not believe there is any need to know theory at all. The important thing is to understand the general plans and ideas. I'll give some lines just to show the ideas, but it is certainly not necessary to remember any of it by heart. }
10. cxd5 exd5
{ This is a likely structure to occur, as White can choose to take on d5 on basically any move. We should make use of our strong e4-outpost by placing a knight there. After that the next step depends a bit on how White proceeds. The important point is to not play c5, as it would actually open more for White's pieces than our own. White's best move would be  11.Rc1  , which is discussed after 10.Rc1. }
11. Ne2 Qe7 12. Ng3
{ This is another common manouver for White, but pay close attention to the next couple of Black moves: }
12... g6 { Restricting the g3-knight. } 13. Qe2 Ne4
{ Centralizing and activating! } 14. Rfc1 h5
{ Intending ...h4, kicking White back. Next up after that, we can either follow up with h3, or just continue bringing our last pieces over to the kingside.  14...f5  would also be normal, but with White's knight already on g3, I like h5 even better. }
