{ 3.g3  doesn't really have any independent value against a6-systems.  3...dxc4!  4.Bg2  a6  White will have to play Nf3 soon, transposing. }
3... a6 4. e3
{ Clearly the most serious of the 4th move alternatives. White is trying to build up in a sort of Colle-style setup with b3, Bb2, Bd3, O-O and Nbd2 or Nc3.  4.cxd5  exd5  will transpose to the mainlines, as White really should play Nc3 here or within the next few moves. }
4... Nf6
{ Basically on our next move we have two ways of playing. We can either try to strike against White's centre immediately, trying to equalize by concrete means. The other option is to choose a setup of how we develop our pieces, and just stick to it. Both options are equally viable, but I quite like the latter option, especially as it goes very well together with our repertoire against alternatives to 2. c4. }
5. b3 b6 { Sticking to our setup. } 6. Bb2 Bb7 7. Bd3 Nbd7 8. O-O Bd6 9. Nbd2
{ 9.Nc3  O-O  is discussed after 5.Nc3. } 9... O-O
{ This is slightly different compared to White having the knight on c3. From d2 it exercises less pressure on d5, but it does defend the f3-knight and the c4-pawn, meaning dxc4 is rarely an option. Therefore ideas with moving the queen to e2 or c2 makes more sense for White here. On the other hand we rarely have to thing about White taking on d5, as it would be the d2-knight dominated by the pawn on d5, and a5-a4 becomes a much more relevant idea as the knight does not cover the a4-square. }
10. Qe2 { By far the most popular move. } 10... a5
{ Always interesting when the knight is committed to d2 rather than c3.  10...Ne4  is the most popular move and also fine. }
11. a4 { This stops the a-pawn further, but does concede a nice square on b4. }
11... Qe7 12. e4 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Bb4
{ White will never be able to play a rook to e1, making it much harder for him to create threats. Next we can go ...Rad8, ...Rfe8 and eventually break with ...c5 or ...e5. }
