[Round "?"]
[White "12) 2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines: 3.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ This is popular at club level. It is easy to play with White as he can develop all pieces peacefully, but on the other hand, so can we as well! I recommend sticking to the setup I suggest against the London as well, with ...Nf6, ...Bd6, ...b6, ...Bb7 and ...Nbd7. }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ 4.c4  is obviously possible, but here we can either transpose with  4...a6!?  or play the immediate  4...b6  , sticking to our setup. }
4... b6
{ Move orders are not of great importance here. We could also have started with  4...Bd6  , but as we are always fianchettoing the c8-bishop we might as well start with it here. }
5. O-O { 5.c4  Bb7  will certainly transpose soon. } 5... Bb7 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2
O-O
{ Generally, as soon as White plays c4 we have an improved version of the 3.Nf3 4.e3 lines, as ...a6 is not the most useful move here. With that in mind it is easy to conclude that the position must be absolutely fine for black. }
8. Nbd2 Ne4 { This can be flicked in at any point, with now being a good one. }
9. c4 Nd7 { This is very comfortable. } 10. Rc1 a5
{ This sees us more or less winning a tempo compared to 3.Nf3 4.e3. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines: 3.e3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. e3
{ This is popular at club level. It is easy to play with White as he can develop all pieces peacefully, but on the other hand, so can we as well! I recommend sticking to the setup I suggest against the London as well, with ...Nf6, ...Bd6, ...b6, ...Bb7 and ...Nbd7. }
3... Nf6 4. Bd3
{ 4.c4  is obviously possible, but here we can either transpose with  4...a6!?  or play the immediate  4...b6  , sticking to our setup. }
4... b6
{ Move orders are not of great importance here. We could also have started with  4...Bd6  , but as we are always fianchettoing the c8-bishop we might as well start with it here. }
5. O-O { 5.c4  Bb7  will certainly transpose soon. } 5... Bb7 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2
O-O
{ Generally, as soon as White plays c4 we have an improved version of the 3.Nf3 4.e3 lines, as ...a6 is not the most useful move here. With that in mind it is easy to conclude that the position must be absolutely fine for black. }
8. Ne5
{ This is probably the most critical move. White is trying to build up some sort of attack on the kingside which we should know how to handle. }
8... c5
{ I like this a lot after after White's Ne5. The point is that as soon as White plays f4, we can make use of the f5-square for our knight. }
9. Nd2 Nc6 10. a3
{ The typical response after ...Nc6.  10.f4  Nb4!?  is annoying for White as the light-squared bishop is absolutely essential for the attack to work. }
10... Ne7
{ The manouver to remember. With the knight coming to the kingside we get an additional defender of our king, making White's 'attack' very unlikely to succeed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines: 4.Bg2 / 5.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ This is actually tricky and should be treated with care! White is trying to play the Catalan, but we can't respond with our usual capture on c4, as White did not put a pawn there yet.  3.Bg5  makes no sense in our move order.  3...Be7  4.Bxe7  Qxe7=  and as is often the case in such positions, the most likely thing to happen is we get positions similar to 3.Nf3 / 4.Bg5, but without having wasted time playing ...a6. }
3... b6
{ Once again we are making use of the tempo gained by not playing ...Nf6. This time we use it to get our bishop to the long diagonal in time.  3...c5  is a decent move and the suggestion of Warmerdam in his Janowsky course, but it leads to mainlines that are in my opinion somewhat outside the scope of our repertoire, and I prefer to avoid them.   3...b5!?  such provocative moves can be played, but to be honest I have always doubted the strength of it. To me, it looks like White should be better.   3...Nf6  4.c4  would be a real Catalan, something we have no intention of entering. }
4. Bg2 Bb7 5. c4 dxc4 { Transposes to 4.c4. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines: 4.Bg2 / 5.O-O / 6.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ This is actually tricky and should be treated with care! White is trying to play the Catalan, but we can't respond with our usual capture on c4, as White did not put a pawn there yet.  3.Bg5  makes no sense in our move order.  3...Be7  4.Bxe7  Qxe7=  and as is often the case in such positions, the most likely thing to happen is we get positions similar to 3.Nf3 / 4.Bg5, but without having wasted time playing ...a6. }
3... b6
{ Once again we are making use of the tempo gained by not playing ...Nf6. This time we use it to get our bishop to the long diagonal in time.  3...c5  is a decent move and the suggestion of Warmerdam in his Janowsky course, but it leads to mainlines that are in my opinion somewhat outside the scope of our repertoire, and I prefer to avoid them.   3...b5!?  such provocative moves can be played, but to be honest I have always doubted the strength of it. To me, it looks like White should be better.   3...Nf6  4.c4  would be a real Catalan, something we have no intention of entering. }
4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O Nd7
{ Important!  5...Nf6?!  6.Ne5!  is unpleasant. After  6...Nbd7  7.c4  Nxe5  8.dxe5!  attacks the knight on f6. }
6. b3 { This is too slow to worry us. } 6... c5 7. Bb2 Ngf6
{ Having solved the main issue of developing the light squared bishop we can proceed to simple development with an equal position. }
*

