[Round "?"]
[White "12) 2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "2.Nf3 3rd Move Sidelines: 4.c4 / 5.Qa4+ #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ This is actually tricky and should be treated with care! White is trying to play the Catalan, but we can't respond with our usual capture on c4, as White did not put a pawn there yet.  3.Bg5  makes no sense in our move order.  3...Be7  4.Bxe7  Qxe7=  and as is often the case in such positions, the most likely thing to happen is we get positions similar to 3.Nf3 / 4.Bg5, but without having wasted time playing ...a6. }
3... b6
{ Once again we are making use of the tempo gained by not playing ...Nf6. This time we use it to get our bishop to the long diagonal in time.  3...c5  is a decent move and the suggestion of Warmerdam in his Janowsky course, but it leads to mainlines that are in my opinion somewhat outside the scope of our repertoire, and I prefer to avoid them.   3...b5!?  such provocative moves can be played, but to be honest I have always doubted the strength of it. To me, it looks like White should be better.   3...Nf6  4.c4  would be a real Catalan, something we have no intention of entering. }
4. c4 { The typical Catalan move. } 4... dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nd7 6. Ne5
{ The critical move. White is trying to plant a knight on the c6-square, one of the very main strategic ideas in the Catalan. }
6... Bb7 7. Nc6 Qc8
{ The knight looks very strong on c6, but we well be able to trade it with Ne7 later on. At first sight it might look unpleasant, but in fact we do not really have any trouble getting our pieces out to where we want them. }
8. Bg2 Bd6 { Important, to prepare our next move. } 9. O-O Ne7
{ Important. We can't let White have his knight on c6 all game! I think the game is just equal as we can't really be stopped from removing the knight and liberating ourselves with ...c5 or ... e5. }
10. Qxc4 O-O 11. Nc3 a6
{ Again preparing the move b5, which will force White to trade his proud c6-knight. }
12. a4 b5 { A useful trick. } 13. axb5 axb5
{ Normally this would win material due to both c4 and a1 hanging, but here White can save himself! }
14. Nxe7+ Bxe7 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. Bxb7 { Leading to a balanced ending. } 16...
bxc4 17. Bxa8 Rxa8
{ The doubled c-pawns are easily compensated for by the weak b2-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
