[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) The Dreaded London System"]
[Black "The Dreaded London System: 4. e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4
{ The dreaded London system. While it's a safe way for White to get all pieces developed it isn't really bothering us too much. The structures that usually arises are familiar to us already, and if anything, we have a slightly improved version of them. I recommend a solid and easy-to-learn system based on developing with ...Bd6, ...Nf6, and then fianchettoing the other bishop to b7. There are a few early move order tricks to keep in mind, but overall I do not think it requires a lot of concrete knowledge. }
3... Bd6
{ The most flexible move order for our repertoire, as the bishop always belongs on d6 while it's not clear if we want our knight on f6 yet.  3...Nf6  4.e3  Bd6  5.Nbd2!?  sees the knight already committed to f6 if we take on f4.   3...c5  eliminates the possibility of us taking with the c-pawn on d6, and commits us to having the pawn on c5 earlier than we might want. }
4. e3
{ Strategically speaking this is an interesting attempt from White. The doubled pawns provides an open e-file and potential to push f4-f5, and if we don't take on f4 White has basically saved a tempo by not having to move his bishop. }
4... Bxf4 5. exf4
{ Normally speaking I'd be hesitant to allow this structure, but here there is a major difference - our knight is not yet comitted to f6. Usually the f6-square is by far the best one for the knight, but specifically in the structure with exf5 we want to be able to put the knight on e7. There are three reasons for this: 1@@EndBracket@@ it prevents White from playing f4-f5. 2@@EndBracket@@ it gives us the possibility of kicking a knight on e5 away with ...f6. 3@@EndBracket@@ it supports the other knight getting to c6. }
5... b6
{ A good way of developing here. We prepare ...c5, but also the trade of bishops with ... Ba6. As the pawns in the centre are placed on light squares our bishop is slightly worse, so we would like to trade it. White now has many moves, but our setup is the same against everything. }
6. Bd3 Qd6
{ Nice to flick in as it threatens both the f4-pawn and a nasty ...Qb4+. } 7.
Qd2 { This is a stupid square for the queen and we can continue as usual. }
7... c5 8. c3 Ba6 { Achieving the generally desirable trade. } 9. Bxa6 Nxa6
{ Please note that Qa4+ would be winning for White here, had we not forced the queen to d2 already! }
10. O-O Ne7 { With the usual kind of play. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) The Dreaded London System"]
[Black "The Dreaded London System: 4. e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4
{ The dreaded London system. While it's a safe way for White to get all pieces developed it isn't really bothering us too much. The structures that usually arises are familiar to us already, and if anything, we have a slightly improved version of them. I recommend a solid and easy-to-learn system based on developing with ...Bd6, ...Nf6, and then fianchettoing the other bishop to b7. There are a few early move order tricks to keep in mind, but overall I do not think it requires a lot of concrete knowledge. }
3... Bd6
{ The most flexible move order for our repertoire, as the bishop always belongs on d6 while it's not clear if we want our knight on f6 yet.  3...Nf6  4.e3  Bd6  5.Nbd2!?  sees the knight already committed to f6 if we take on f4.   3...c5  eliminates the possibility of us taking with the c-pawn on d6, and commits us to having the pawn on c5 earlier than we might want. }
4. e3
{ Strategically speaking this is an interesting attempt from White. The doubled pawns provides an open e-file and potential to push f4-f5, and if we don't take on f4 White has basically saved a tempo by not having to move his bishop. }
4... Bxf4 5. exf4
{ Normally speaking I'd be hesitant to allow this structure, but here there is a major difference - our knight is not yet comitted to f6. Usually the f6-square is by far the best one for the knight, but specifically in the structure with exf5 we want to be able to put the knight on e7. There are three reasons for this: 1@@EndBracket@@ it prevents White from playing f4-f5. 2@@EndBracket@@ it gives us the possibility of kicking a knight on e5 away with ...f6. 3@@EndBracket@@ it supports the other knight getting to c6. }
5... b6
{ A good way of developing here. We prepare ...c5, but also the trade of bishops with ... Ba6. As the pawns in the centre are placed on light squares our bishop is slightly worse, so we would like to trade it. White now has many moves, but our setup is the same against everything. }
6. Nbd2 Ne7
{ We generally wait for White to lose a tempo with the bishop before trading it on a6. }
7. Bd3 Ba6
{ A good move now that White has wasted a move on Bd3.  7...c5  8.c3  a5  followed by ...Ba6 is also reasonable. }
8. Bxa6 Nxa6 9. Qe2
{ Forcing our knight back, but the best square for it is anyway on c6 @@StartBracket@@after we have played ...c5@@EndBracket@@ so we don't mind. }
9... Nb8 10. O-O O-O
{ Followed by ...c5 and ...Nbc6. White struggles to find a good pawn break, especially as our e7-knight controls f5. Later on, we can try to open the c-file and get counterplay there. Another reasonable plan is to push the queenside pawns. But the main thing to understand is that we are in no hurry, as White is far away from creating threats. }
