{ This move has been played against me in a similar position. Once I took with the queen and once with the pawn. Both are fine, but I recommend something simple. }
4... Qxd6 5. c4 { This is White's idea. } 5... Nf6 6. e3 O-O
{ But here we have a position similar to 3. Nf3 4. Bg5, but without having had to play ...a6. }
7. c5 Qe7 8. Nc3
{ This can be a scary structure for Black if it is not possible to break out. Here though we will have an easy time getting ...e5 in, creating enough counterplay. }
8... Nbd7 9. b4 c6 10. Be2 e5
{ Next is either ...e4 or even ...Ne4, in both cases creating some counterplay on the kingside. Without real weaknesses and our bishop having an easy time getting out soon, we have nothing to complain about. }
*

