[White "13) The Dreaded London System"]
[Black "The Dreaded London System: 4.Bg3 / 6.Nbd2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4
{ The dreaded London system. While it's a safe way for White to get all pieces developed it isn't really bothering us too much. The structures that usually arises are familiar to us already, and if anything, we have a slightly improved version of them. I recommend a solid and easy-to-learn system based on developing with ...Bd6, ...Nf6, and then fianchettoing the other bishop to b7. There are a few early move order tricks to keep in mind, but overall I do not think it requires a lot of concrete knowledge. }
3... Bd6
{ The most flexible move order for our repertoire, as the bishop always belongs on d6 while it's not clear if we want our knight on f6 yet.  3...Nf6  4.e3  Bd6  5.Nbd2!?  sees the knight already committed to f6 if we take on f4.   3...c5  eliminates the possibility of us taking with the c-pawn on d6, and commits us to having the pawn on c5 earlier than we might want. }
4. Bg3
{ The most natural and common move. We do not want to take on g3, as the open h-file is rather useful for White, especially before having castled. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This would be the auto-pilot move.  6.Bd3  is similar to this and likely to transpose,  6...b6  keeps the most life in the position.  7.Ne5  Bb7  and White should really played  8.Nd2  here, transposing. }
6... b6
{ 6...c5  can be played as well.  7.dxc5  Bxc5  8.c4  see our 6.c4 line. } 7.
Bd3 Bb7
{ Basically we do not really need to know anymore concrete theory here. We plan to play ...Nbd7 and ...Ne4, with ...c5 flicked in at some point. White has spent two moves putting his bishop on g3, but I actually prefer our fianchettoed one on b7!  7...Ba6  is also possible, but I like our bishop on  b7  , supporting a later Ne4. }
8. Ne5
{ This has historically been the most common move. This is slightly more testing, as White intends to follow up with f4 and create an initiative on the kingside.  8.Qe2  Ne4  followed by  ...Nd7  is similar. }
8... Ne4
{ Again works very well. It's important to not let White build up their attack indisturbed with f4, Qf3 etc after which it can quickly get dangerous.  8...Nbd7  9.f4  Ne4  would be the more typical response, and also works well. }
9. f4
{ 9.Qh5  is not really threatening anything, we play  9...Nd7  and next we can kick the queen away with ...Ndf6 or even simpler, just trade on  e5  . }
9... f6
{ Shows why I don't want to rush with ...Nd7 as Black. The e5-knight is forced to a clumsy square. }
10. Ng4 c5
{ Gives excellent counterplay in the centre. Note that the e4-knight really blocks all the White attemps at creating an attack. }
