1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. Bf4
{ The dreaded London system. While it's a safe way for White to get all pieces developed it isn't really bothering us too much. The structures that usually arises are familiar to us already, and if anything, we have a slightly improved version of them. I recommend a solid and easy-to-learn system based on developing with ...Bd6, ...Nf6, and then fianchettoing the other bishop to b7. There are a few early move order tricks to keep in mind, but overall I do not think it requires a lot of concrete knowledge. }
3... Bd6
{ The most flexible move order for our repertoire, as the bishop always belongs on d6 while it's not clear if we want our knight on f6 yet.  3...Nf6  4.e3  Bd6  5.Nbd2!?  sees the knight already committed to f6 if we take on f4.   3...c5  eliminates the possibility of us taking with the c-pawn on d6, and commits us to having the pawn on c5 earlier than we might want. }
4. Bg3
{ The most natural and common move. We do not want to take on g3, as the open h-file is rather useful for White, especially before having castled. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O 6. c4
{ The critical move and typical for the modern treatment of the London, where White is not just making all the moves on auto-pilot, but actually tries to be a bit smart. }
6... c5
{ We actually have a slight lead in development, so this makes a lot of sense.  6...b6  would transpose to 5...b6  . }
7. cxd5 { Trying to saddle us with an IQP. } 7... exd5 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. dxc5
Qxc5 10. Be2 { A cunning move order. } 10... Nc6 11. O-O Rd8 12. Nbd2
{ White's point. By going Nbd2-b3 he is in time to stop us from playing ...d4. }
12... Qe7 { Intending ...d4. } 13. Nb3 Ne4
{ Ok, White managed to stop ...d4, but at the expense of a clear plan. I believe we can make use of our space advantage by going for an attack on the kingside while still keeping the centre safe. }
14. Nbd4
{ This would keep the f3-knight defending the king, but we can still go for our plan. }
14... Rd6 15. Rc1 Rg6
{ With decent counterplay. Again, the reason we can permit ourselves such maneuvers is that we have the centre firmly under control with our pawn on d5 and knight on e4.  15...h5!?  even this is interesting! }
*

