1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Bg5
{ Frankly speaking a pretty bad move. Any normal developing move will lead to a pleasant position, but personally, I like to punish White. }
2... f6
{ I understand this looks a bit unnatural, and it is a very concrete move. I think it leads to an edge for Black, but if you don't feel like it's worth it to study theory after 2. Bg5, then any other move is perfectly sensible as well. For example,  2...h6  3.Bh4  c6  just setting up a solid centre. After  4.Nd2  Bf5  our bishop is outside the pawn chain, this is very solid for Black. However, it's a lot less fun than our mainline! }
3. Bh4
{ 3.Bf4  is not quite the Jobava-London with colours reversed, as we can still play ...c5 before ...Nc6. Again, White has basically just wasted one tempo by moving the bishop twice. }
3... Nh6
{ This is the big point. With the bishop on h4 we can attack it immediately with a knight on f5. }
4. f3
{ Gives the bishop a square on f2, but weakens the dark squares, which we can utilize with our next move. }
4... c5 5. dxc5 e6 { Keeping d5 solid while retaking the c5-pawn. } 6. Bf2 Nd7
{ Followed by ....Bxc5, with a nice edge as White is both underdeveloped and lacks control over the centre. }
