1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. e4
{ The Blackmar-Diemer. One of the less sound gambits, but still played from time to time. I have even managed to lose a classical game against it a few years back! }
2... dxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. f3
{ This is White's idea. I am sure taking the pawn on f3 also gives Black an edge here, but for practical purposes, I prefer the very simple. }
4... Bf5
{ This might objectively give a slightly smaller edge, but a very comfortable and easy-to-play one. }
5. g4 Bg6 6. g5
{ Would actually transpose to2. Nc3 if we put our knight on the rim, but in this situation, we can instead go to the centre. }
6... Nd5 7. Nxe4 e6
{ White's position simply doesn't make any sense. Basically, the pawn on g5 does not disturb our coordination at all but rather gives us some nice squares on f4, f5 and h5. Meanwhile, we are ahead in development and will soon start attacking the centre. }
*

