1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Bf4 e6 3. e3 Bd6
{ This is very similar to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  e6  3.Bf4  but there are some small differences. }
4. Qg4 { The independent try, making use of not having played Nf3 yet. } 4...
g6
{ White is trying to claim that g6 is a weakness. It probably is, but but on the other hand the queen moved out a bit too early, losing some valuable time. }
5. Qf3 { Avoiding our threat of ...e5. } 5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ The most dangerous move. White is intending to castle long.  6.Bd3  Nc6  intending ...e5 looks sensible. White suffers from the fact that Nf3 is not possible. }
6... Nbd7
{ Waiting for White to commit the king.  6...Nc6?!  7.O-O-O!  stops ...e5 but is a bit unpleasant! }
7. O-O-O
{ 7.Bxd6  cxd6  gives us a doubled pawn, but generally speaking the doubled pawn is not so bad, as it keeps control of many of the central squares. Additionally, we also get a semi-open c-file to use for counterplay if White castles long. }
7... a6
{ Initiating counterplay with ...b5-b4 - often a good plan in d4-d5 positions when White castles long. }
8. e4
{ This would be logical to open the centre up, but ends up being very solid for us... }
8... Nxe4 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Qxe4 Nf6 11. Qf3 Nd5 { Avoiding the Bg5 pin. } 12.
Bxd6
{ 12.Bh6  is nonsense due to  12...Qh4!  and the h6-bishop has to retreat again. }
12... cxd6
{ We have a harmonious position. Next up could be either ...b5 followed by ...Bb7, or just simple development with ...Bd7. }
