[Black "Veresov 3.f3 / 4.Bg5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nc3
{ The Veresov. Generally speaking the sidelines on move 2 works better for White against 1...Nf6 than 1...d5, as we now often can make use of not having our knight on f6 yet. }
2... Bf5
{ I like this a lot! Usually we have to struggle a lot to develop our bishop so easily, but here we get a chance to do it 'for free'. The only downside of this is that White can now attack our bishop with f3 and g4, but I think it does more harm than good to White's position.  2...c5  is another good moves, but it allows  3.e4!?  dxe4  4.d5  which is fine for Black but not to everyone's taste. }
3. f3
{ Clearly the critical move. The only way to 'punish' ...Bf5 is to attack it with e4 or g4. }
3... Nf6 { Now necessary, in order to stop e4. } 4. Bg5
{ This is a bit of a strange mix between systems for White, as after g4 the pawn often wants to progress to g5. }
4... Nbd7 { 4...c6  to avoid White's trick is very solid as well! } 5. Nxd5
{ The only real point of what White is doing. Still, it does not work out too well for White... }
5... Nxd5 6. e4 { Because we have the very strong intermediate move. } 6... h6
{ And both bishop retreats contains major drawbacks. } 7. Bh4 N7b6
{ A good reply - utilizing a hidden tactical possibility! } 8. c3
{ The main tactical point is that after  8.exf5?  we have  8...Ne3  9.Qd3  Qxd4!  with a very dominant position.   So,  8.c3  is necessary, but we are certainly very comfortable... }
8... Bh7 9. exd5 Qxd5
{ Followed by ...O-O-O and later preparing ...e5. Again, an important factor here is that the move f3 makes no sense at all for White, and it would have much better for him to have a knight there instead. }
