[White "14) Jobava Attack & 2nd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Accelerated Jobava 3.f3 / 4.g4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5
{ Immediately fighting for the center, making this the most classical move. That perhaps sounds vague, but it is important for what is to come. Basically, by already placing a pawn in the center, we make sure of at least some central control making it much less likely we get rolled over, unlike for example the King's Indian or the Grunfeld, where Black gives up the center early on.   This in turn means that we can allow ourselves more freedom later, which we will really use in a provocative way in this repertoire! }
2. Nc3
{ The Veresov. Generally speaking the sidelines on move 2 works better for White against 1...Nf6 than 1...d5, as we now often can make use of not having our knight on f6 yet. }
2... Bf5
{ I like this a lot! Usually we have to struggle a lot to develop our bishop so easily, but here we get a chance to do it 'for free'. The only downside of this is that White can now attack our bishop with f3 and g4, but I think it does more harm than good to White's position.  2...c5  is another good moves, but it allows  3.e4!?  dxe4  4.d5  which is fine for Black but not to everyone's taste. }
3. f3
{ Clearly the critical move. The only way to 'punish' ...Bf5 is to attack it with e4 or g4. }
3... Nf6 { Now necessary, in order to stop e4. } 4. g4
{ The most ambitious move. } 4... Bg6 5. g5
{ This is again a critical attempt, as the pawn on d5 is hanging if ...Nfd7. }
5... Nh5
{ Now the pawn on g5 is rather badly placed, but our knight on h5 can also become a liability. }
6. e4
{ White is pushing with everything he got. It is of course tempting, but also very likely to backfire. }
6... dxe4 7. f4
{ Looks horrible, but it does threaten Be2 or f5, both picking up our knight on h5! }
7... e5
{ A fantastic move! it is simply imperative that we develop as quickly as possible. }
8. fxe5 Nc6
{ 8...h6  9.Qg4  Qd7  is a calmer way to play, with a strategically very messy ending. }
9. Be3
{ 9.Be2  does not win a piece as  9...Nxd4  and if White takes twice on h5, the c2 pawn will hang with threats of a fork on the king and rook! }
9... Bb4 { Not fearing for our knight! } 10. Be2
{ certainly the critical move, but now White's lack of development will tell for real. }
10... Ne7
{ Another fantastic way of generating counterplay. The knight is heading for d5. }
11. Bxh5 Nd5 { With a very scary initiative. } 12. Bxg6
{ This is the only move for White not to collapse, but it works well for us... }
12... Nxe3 13. Qd2 Qxg5 { The bishop on g6 is actually trapped! } 14. Bxe4 Bxc3
15. Qxc3 Qh4+ 16. Kd2 Qxe4
{ The point - winning the piece back with a very comfortable position. } 17.
Ne2 Nd5
{ White might still be OK, but in practical play, I definitely prefer Black's position. We can castle long and begin play in the centre. }
