[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises"]
[Black "Exercise #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rr4k1/1p3p2/p1pq1npp/2Np1n2/PP1P4/4PN1P/2Q2PP1/R4RK1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ In this position, what is White's main plan? After having played a4 and b4, they are intending on pushing b5. What's the solution? }
1... Qc7 { The purpose of this move is two-fold! Now, if White prepares b5... }
2. Rab1
{ If White pushes b5 immediately...   2.b5  cxb5  The knight is now pinned to the Queen! Now if White takes back..  3.axb5  b6  Black wins a piece due to the pin on the knight! }
2... Nd6
{ We've talked a lot about the strength of the d6 Knight in this course! Here, it stops b5 and leaves White struggling to come up with a decent plan. Continue studyinghere! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises"]
[Black "Exercise #2 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r4rk1/1p2qp1p/pnp1bnp1/3p4/3P4/P1NBPN1P/1PQ2PP1/2R1R1K1 b - - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ What is our general plan in Carlsbad structures, and how should we go about executing it? }
1... Nc8
{ Bringing the Knight back to d6, and trading our passive bishop for White's good bishop on f5! This will make it much easier for our knights to start maneouvering, and we should soon be able to start our play on the kingside. The f6 knight was already well placed and will eventually want to go to e4, so we use the b6 knight which was not contributing as much to our position!   1...Rfe8  The engine also likes this move and @@StartFEN@@r4rk1/1p2qp1p/pnp1bnp1/3p4/3P4/P1NBPN1P/1PQ2PP1/2R1R1K1 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1...Kg7  , but the point of this exercise is to show strategic ideas in the Carlsbad. Continue Studyinghere! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises"]
[Black "Exercise #3 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnb1k2r/1pp2pp1/p2q1n1p/3p4/3P4/2N1PN1P/PP3PP1/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White hasn't prevented us from acting on a key idea we usually get in our variations. What idea is it? }
1... Bf5
{ Normally speaking, White is always quick to put a bishop on d3 or a queen on c2 to prevent our light squared bishop from being developed in order to cover this square! Our big problem with the bishop can now be solved, and the only thing that can scare us now would be... }
2. Qb3
{ But here, White is too far behind in development and we have a typical reply! }
2... O-O { Giving the b7 pawn away! If White takes it... } 3. Qxb7 Nc6
{ We develop our Knight and threaten to play ...Rfb8! trapping the queen. White has to move the queen, but is now very far behind in time. }
4. Qb3 Rab8 { We now threaten to take the b2 pawn! } 5. Qa3 Nb4
{ With threats of ...Nc2 forking everything! The White position is slowly collapsing. Continue Studyinghere! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Exercises"]
[Black "Exercise #4 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "1n1qk2r/rp2bppp/p1p1b3/8/3PN3/P4N2/1PQ2PPP/2KR1B1R b k - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ White has played in a very aggressive fashion, castling queenside and now waiting for us to castle kingside so they can initiate some play with h4 and maybe Ng5. What should we do instead? }
1... b5 { Getting counterplay against White's king instead, and stopping Bc4! }
2. Bd3
{ Developing the bishop, but now we push our b-pawn further up the board! }
2... b4 { Now if White recaptures... } 3. axb4 { 3.a4  b3 } 3... Bxb4
{ We have strong counterplay, with ideas of pushing our a pawn all the way up to a3 - which is really annoying for White to deal with. The line in the theoretical section ends here, but you can continue studying similar positions in the followingvariations! }
*

