[Black "Exercise #7 "]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "bn1qr1k1/2p2ppp/4p3/1p6/1B1Pn3/3NP3/1P2BPPP/3QK2R b K - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ If White now gets the time to bring his king to safety, and maybe the kick the knight away with f3, we'll have serious strategic problems. White will have the two bishops and our pawn on c7 will become quite weak - it's imperative for us to act quickly! }
1... c5
{ Trying to break free with a strong sacrifice - activating our position and creating a lot of counterplay with tactical possibilities. }
2. Nxc5
{ The more critical capture!  If White takes with the pawn...   2.dxc5  Na6  intending to take the bishop on b4 and then the pawn on c5, either with the knight or with the queen after ...Qg5. }
2... Nxc5 3. dxc5
{ A trickier attempt!  If White takes back with the bishop...   3.Bxc5  Bxg2  Winning back the pawn, but more importantly keeping the White king in the centre while trading off our weak pawn. }
3... Qg5
{ The best move! After  3...Bxg2  , White is in time to trade the queens and the resulting endgame is unpleasant for us. Now, White can no longer castle and we're hitting the pawn on g2 again. }
4. Bf3 Na6
{ Hitting the bishop and pawn, and now we have no problems whatsoever and even material. Continue studyinghere! }
